[{'created': '2015-04-15 11:46:17.000000000', 'message': "Port Removal handling

Port removal is designed to be agnostic to the purpose of the flows.
It uses a Bloom Filter [1] to select the flows to be removed. We can
handle mismatches since if valid flow was removed it will be recreated
by the controller on next packet.

This puts the responsibility of marking the flow on the flow creator.
When creating a flow, it's important that the cookie contain a filter
built from all the ports that need to exist for the flow to remain
active.

To create a proper filter one should use the provided CookieFilter()
class. Specifically CookieFilter.from_route([port1, port2, ...]).

The values used are the values returned from PortData.cookie_hash.

[1] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bloom_filter

Change-Id: I10fd206b2ad8875ec7a2f9abdb9d13e74ea0cb77
Signed-off-by: Saggi Mizrahi <saggi.mizrahi@huawei.com>

commit_message:
Port Removal handling

Only handles events generated from ovs itself. Future patches will
handle events generated from Neutron

Port removal is designed to be agnostic to the purpose of the flows.
It uses a Bloom Filter [1] to select the flows to be removed. We can
handle mismatches since if valid flow was removed it will be recreated
by the controller on next packet.This puts the responsibility of marking
the flow on the flow creator.
When creating a flow, it's important that the cookie contain a filter
built from all the ports that need to exist for the flow to remain
active.To create a proper filter one should use the provided
CookieFilter()
class. Specifically CookieFilter.from_route([port1, port2, ...]).The
values used are the values returned from PortData.cookie_hash.

[1] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bloom_filter

Change-Id: I10fd206b2ad8875ec7a2f9abdb9d13e74ea0cb77

Why should entity names be mandatory? That seems beyond the scope of this bug. I think creating things without names and just referring to them with the UUID values is a legitimate use case. Thought that would be slightly contentious. 

@Adrian: Bay models are going to be 'pets' which I think deserve real names, perhaps containers and bays are more like 'cattle' and don't deserve a real name. In nova all instances have to have a name and I was following that model."}, {'account_id': 11650, 'date': '2015-05-01 17:06:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-05-01 17:18:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

Thanks! This revision looks like a good match to what the bug calls for. My suggestion is to table the mandatory name attributes until we identify a reason to require the names.

Our API's should allow a consistent style of use compared to other OpenStack services. That means we should not make our API burdensome by requiring a totally different usage style. On the subject of mandatory attributes, as long as our default is permissive to allow consistent style of use (which this patch does), we meet the expectation for consistency. In other words, nothing is stopping users from specifying names even tough they are not required.

We can actually require name attributes in the future if we find a compelling reason."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-01 17:45:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fix translation steps

Today's nova import had some file changes where only the
POT-Creation-Date was changed which we don't need to import.

With the new compression step, we need to filter out commits *after* the
compression, otherwise counting is wrong.

Change-Id: Ib8fe6ca5f77c805147b73fe94905c72ccf3369d4

Hi Monty,

I think Fei Long and Stuart had excellent points there.

I can recognize good intention behind this but I fail to see the definite benefits versus risks. As Stuart pointed out your logic fails as uploading the image to glance is single command operation from client already at the moment.

First thing I'm wondering is how I manage to fail to find this import functionality from Glance API server side. Could you point me to right track on this?

My main concern is related to the one Feil Long has, this functionality being only for swift deployments and specially the hard dependency to swiftclient in glanceclient.

@erno

> benefits versus risks

For public clouds the vast majority of users do not have the privileges required to directly upload; they must use import. Currently that will involve several steps and different clients. The intention here I think is to make it more straightforward.

Adding Brian -- he's probably got some good insights here."}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2015-04-15 16:55:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hello everyone,

Monty, I agree with Erno's suggestion that we discuss this on a spec first.  I completely sympathize with your desire to make this a simpler operation from the end-user's point of view, but I'm not sure what's the best way to go about it, and I have some reservations about your particular solution.  (I numbered the following for reference, they're not in any particular order.)

(1) The --poll option is a nice idea, but with tasks we could be talking about a long period of time (on the order of 10s of minutes), especially if you include the image data upload as part of the process.  Getting, say, 35GB into swift over public internet takes a while, and then you have any provider-defined import processing as well.  I think tasks are more a kind of "go down to the corner coffee shop and check when you come back" thing.  But that's just me.

(2) I agree with Fei Long that this looks too customized.  It just so happens that at Rackspace we use swift both for object store and as the backend for glance, but we could use different technologies for either of those.  The import workflow we've architected is that an end-user (a) uploads the image data to the cloud object store, then (b) creates an import task.  The import task then uses the customer's credentials to pull the data from the object store, do some processing on it, and then creates an image in Glance.

(3) I agree with Stuart, by the way, that Glance doesn't necessarily want to get out of the image-storage business.  Glance needs to maintain consistency between the image records and the image data.

(4) When tasks were designed (during the Icehouse cycle, iirc), the idea was that we wanted a simple interface that would be common across all openstack deployments, but that would also be customizable because providers would have different requirements based on the type of images used in their clouds, etc.  But that may have left things too wide open, because while the task schema is the same across providers, there's no guarantee that the "input" element of an import task for Cloud A will be recognized by Cloud B.  (I don't see any way around that, but that may be a failure of imagination on my part.)

(5) I realize that it's a PITA not to be able to just upload your image to Glance, but that functionality is there, and private clouds may want to expose it directly to end-users.  For the public cloud situation, I don't think Glance is built for holding multiple simultaneous connections of various speeds, so I don't even want to try that.  I figure an OpenStack-wide solution would be to let end-users put the image data in the cloud's object store, which is designed for handling holding multiple simultaneous connections of various speeds over the public internet, and then the import task just needs to get the data from the object store, do whatever processing is desired, and then create the image.  So I guess what I'm saying is that we want to change end-user expectations from "hey, I want to upload an image to Glance" to recognizing that the workflow is to put your putative image into your cloud's object store, and then ask Glance to import it.

(6) Also, the design discussion around tasks recognized that these are likely to be high-error operations (e.g., end-users uploading JPEGs or other invalid stuff), so the image creation only happens at the end of the import operation.  (That's why the tasks were designed to be independent objects.)  Not sure why I mentioned this, it seemed important a minute ago.

I've gone on too long. I agree it would be nice to have a more straightforward way to import images.  On the other hand, I think that we should reframe the issue: in a public cloud, you shouldn't expect to "upload" an image in the first place.  You should expect to "import" it from your cloud's object store.  But I guess what I'm worried about is that if we try to make the entire workflow into a single operation, as this patch would do, it's going to be really annoying to customers because it's going to take a long time and may not result in an image being created.  I'd like to see the problem of getting the image from your laptop into the cloud separated from the problem of creating an image out of whatever that thing is you uploaded.  I don't want to see Glance be blamed for the first problem.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-04-21 19:32:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thank you for the very thorough response. It is helpful and   will start working on specs.

However, I'd like to disagree with one thing here:

"in a public cloud, you shouldn't expect to "upload" an image in the first place. You should expect to "import" it from your cloud's object store"

There are two problems with that.

One is that I'm a user and you're telling me I have the wrong expectations. That's something we as OpenStack need to do less. Instead, I think we should listen to our users, understand their expectations, and either provide them, or provide something _else_ which is not easy to mistake for a bad solution to their original expectations.

The second is that not all clouds have object stores. Not even all public clouds (neither RunAbove nor vexxhost have object stores) They DO all have Glance, and glance is always where the images go. That there are two different ways to get an image into glance based on choices a deployer made about services that have nothing to do with images is more than confusing. That we have no way to communicate that the user should use one API in one place and a different API in a different place is a failure on our part as OpenStack, and we should endeavor to fix it.

Perhaps we could add an API call to glance that returns whether or not a user should use image-upload or task-import?

Or perhaps glance image-upload should return a 301 if swift should be used?

Or perhaps something more clever?

In any case - that's fodder for a spec, which I'll start working on soon.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-05-03 12:09:47.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add task-upload command for uploading images in v2

There are several complicated steps involved with uploading an image
successfully in the glance v2 API. Provide an all-in-one command that
does these steps, with an optional "--poll" options modeled after the
nova --poll options which will poll the task status and ultimately print
the image dict.

This change adds python-swiftclient as a hard dependency, because even
if a user does not want to use the task-upload command, swiftclient _IS_
a hard dependency for anyone who wants to upload an image with v2.

Change-Id: Ifd2fb913284a56684a4ed3611f743e5ad0645137

commit_message:
Add missing docstring in direct_client

Added a missing docstring to the direct_delete_container method.

Also checked other docstrings in the same file and fixed a wrong docstring
element in direct_delete_object. Added raises: docstring entry to all methods
that raise an Exception.

Change-Id: If463a0f9ddff3fe2d13f6d97fcfa955e91d0f01f

commit_message:
Remove is_active property from SimpleInterfaceMonitor

is_active property from SimpleInterfaceMonitor shadows
the method is_active inherited from AsyncProcess.
The property checks that ovsdb monitor is running and
that it received some data. When ovsdb monitor starts
it always receives data, since it processes the interfaces
present on the machine, so the flag data_received will
always be set to true right after SimpleInterfaceMonitor
starts. Considering that, is_active can be removed and
the method is_active inherited from AsyncProcess can be
used instead.

Change-Id: I05faeddd061ab45af51c044a10462c3a57593d4d

commit_message:
Configure API-based plugin unit tests

The API-based Kilo plugin is not configured to run unit tests properly,
which caused the following issues:

 * A bug in lbaas API
 * DHCP extra options not implemented

Change-Id: I479372e4f2c46dc0c4285a485c38829643c08ec7
Fixes: MNP-117

commit_message:
Make vmtasks network_wrapper code less wonky

The VM utils module used some wonky code to get a persistent network
wrapper object, which is not necessary and reduces code
readability. This removes said code.

Change-Id: Ifb336ecb4c65a7eab0294fa13fae793ac72fb9de

commit_message:
Update devstack default to only use IPv4

Devstack was recently changed to use IPv4 and IPv6 (dual stacked)
as default.

Change-Id: I17221d2199f29af2bb5c762df79a68af3ca9ca34
Fixes: MNP-118

commit_message:
Add tempest-dsvm-sahara

Because sahara builds on the compute base layer, it does not need to be
tested in all devstack-gate jobs. Instead create a new job that tests
sahara in a devstack environment as a first step in removing it from the
standard configuration.

Specify that SAHARA should be enabled in the devstack updown job
so that the parts that enable sahara are exercised in devstack.
This is already currently the case, but this updates the job config
so that it will continue to do so later when we remove sahara from
the default config.

Change-Id: Iae4e2439bfdfe7f3fc5f0b75b38583a70d7d78f4
Co-Authored-By: James E. Blair <jeblair@hp.com>

Print Rally debug logs in Rally dsvm gate jobs

Add --rally-debug flag to the task execution to show
 rally logs in scenarios that are tested on gate.

commit_message:
Get all interfaces for get_snat_sync_interfaces

The get_snat_sync_interfaces method was being called for
each router individually during a sync, which resulted
in a new query to the database.

This patch eliminates that waste by querying for the snat
interfaces for all of the routers in the list at once.

Change-Id: I1e44a0cf15a70632e8b62ac89ce807a7a457747d
Partial-Bug: #1445412

commit_message:
Replace exec calls with cryptography library

Many places where the openssl command line is executed can be
replaced with the newer cryptography library that provides
openssl bindings.

Depends-On: I98941cce82d3c33bcc95ecc48ecff413ef81664a

Change-Id: Id18fe9f8488204e73d063d7771357eced82e441f

commit_message:
Admin extends tenant's volume but change admin's quota

When admin extends a tenant's volume, the tenant's
quota-usage doesn't change. However, admin's quota-usage
has changed. The right practice is: extend whose volume,
whose quota-usage should be changed.

Change-Id: Ia1bed7f212cbee715e29698ebbfe3c67486a55f5
Closes-Bug: #1421492

commit_message:
Fix exception re-raise during task execution for py34

This is the code fragment from six (executed when the interpreter is
python 3):

    def reraise(tp, value, tb=None):
        if value is None:
            value = tp()
        if value.__traceback__ is not tb:
            raise value.with_traceback(tb)
        raise value

We want `raise value` or `raise value.with_traceback(tb)` to be
executed as we are invoking six.reraise with a class instance.

Change-Id: Ic0c7e14cecb1cbdcb8cae87047e20514c4d38301

commit_message:
Make warlock filtering match dict filtering

For obj_to_dict, we filter out keys that start with _ and values that
are not normal values. Do the same for our warlock conversion.

Change-Id: Idbf4303c1e4151494d1ea814be6ca5f86e76b16d

commit_message:
Make test_version_string_with_package_is_good work with pbr 0.11

nova.version uses the version_string() API not version. Fix the test to
reflect that and make it work with pbr 0.11

Closes-Bug: #1450682
Change-Id: I4887b8000c9943c91f8add56fcc54fa18e78d683

commit_message:
Add more tests for server metadata processing

Make sure that each of the things we do in get_hostvars_for_server is
checked as working. In walking through it, found a bug in image ids from
boot-from-volume servers.

Change-Id: If71d2cd114c5b5406a39dbb04c96b61fc7193399

commit_message:
Add early service fail and active check method

To make things clearer - do an active check at each client instantiation
to make sure that the service exists in the catalog so that we can throw
a clear error. Also, add a method that can be used for switching on
things like "if neutron: neutron-floating-ips: else: nova-floating-ips"
that doesn't have to do a REST roundtrip to find the failure.

Change-Id: I43b32fff56e09f31bd6d6845b3bf9b5414632651

In the DevStack caching script/element for Nodepool images, use
run_local instead of subprocess.check_output in the _find_images
function. The latter wasn't introduced until Python 2.7 and so won't

"}]
commit_message:
Replace subprocess with run_local in _find_images

In the DevStack caching script/element for Nodepool images, use
run_local instead of subprocess.check_output in the _find_images
function. The latter wasn't introduced until Python 2.7 and so won't
work on CentOS 6. The script called from this function returns
quickly and doesn't benefit from non-blocking I/O anyway.

Change-Id: I3129f1f5b3fece321ae132ea1a52b0e156e58365

commit_message:
Add /usr/local/bin to exec_dirs in rootwrap.conf

devstack installs some utilities into /usr/local/bin such as
ebrctl. This patch adds /usr/local/bin into exec_dirs to allow
rootwrap  to search executables in this directory.

Closes-Bug: #1451018

Change-Id: I7423c3ba1bd12dc696543fc8c2275047e61a8879

commit_message:
Add a method for getting an endpoint

There are a couple of different things you need to get the right
endpoint. We know them all, but the logic is spread out. Consolidate.
Also, put the silly keystone-specific logic there, rather than in
keystone_client.

Change-Id: Ide66c62fe0babddb1530b4f3472a6aeb9713917a

commit_message:
Raise a shade exception on broken volumes

Some clouds don't have volumes and bomb out here, which is a bad place
to bomb out. A later patch will add an active check for service
existence, but we still should catch and throw here so that we're not
leaking python-*client exceptions.

Change-Id: I1f768dcd6ad6f54fb1b5638e9486653ee07965ef

commit_message:
Split exceptions into their own file

We were getting to the point where we were making some circular depends.
Clear that up by splitting the exceptions into their own file.

We're importing * to keep the external interface in the ansible modules.

Change-Id: I1d804377c3cd4eebcc94624902f9e5ec6ebf9321

commit_message:
Add thread sync points to Task

Although the default behavior of Task is to return immediately in shade,
the reason it's abstracted at all is to facilitate multi-threaded
rate-limited TaskManagers such as the one found in nodepool. In order
for those to work, we kind of need the wait conditions to actual do
something.

Change-Id: Icce9729aa2f8f31931dd9d3723d9d5d758436fa9

[{'created': '2015-05-02 07:11:56.000000000', 'message': 'Handle empty translation files

We have some strange files in the tree that contain no or little
translation after merging - and these are downloaded from transifex.
So, these files are not known to git and git rm fails.
To not special case every git rm and git reset for both old and new
files, re-add a "git add" at the beginning so that we can operate on
files known to git.

Note: This happens when we have a file like glance-log-critical.po that has no
strings - but we had to create it with initial content in transifex,
since empty files are not allowed there.

Change-Id: Ie9bb3e59560d50829e56928b2ed79e3999dd39cb
'}]
commit_message:
Handle empty translation files

We have some strange files in the tree that contain no or little
translation after merging - and these are downloaded from transifex.
So, these files are not known to git and git rm fails.
To not special case every git rm and git reset for both old and new
files, re-add a "git add" at the beginning so that we can operate on
files known to git.

Note: This happens when we have a file like glance-log-critical.po that has no
strings - but we had to create it with initial content in transifex,
since empty files are not allowed there.

Change-Id: Ie9bb3e59560d50829e56928b2ed79e3999dd39cb

commit_message:
Remove hacking from oslo channel

The hacking project is managed by the QA team, so changes don't need to
be posted to the Oslo channel any more.

Change-Id: If664ff73958da27aa7408eab31b9a164c03eb799

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/169642/'}, {'account_id': 9498, 'date': '2015-04-09 16:42:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Srinivas, thanks for letting me know of the dictionary comparison you already implemented. Two things though:
1. If I were to use it I think it should be moved to a utility class or something.
2. As I responded to Idan on my patch set 2 to his comment about using the built-in comparison, the reason I did not use the built-in compare method is that the comparison we should perform is a special one. There are certain lists in the resulting HOT spec for which the order of elements is not important. For example, "allowed_values" and "depends_on". Since we cannot control the order of their values out of the translator we need to tweak the comparison to ignore the order so test cases always pass (instead of randomly failing). Can you please confirm whether your code addresses this special case?'}, {'account_id': 9498, 'date': '2015-04-10 18:17:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Patch Set 4 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-10 18:27:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

supported, as described in bug #1440247. As a result of the change in

well. It is important to bring back the removed code and revert the
changes made to wordpress TOSCA file as part of the patch for bug

commit_message:
Create a unit test for wordpress specification in TOSCA

Create a TOSCA-HOT translation unit test template and use that to
unit test TOSCA wordpress example.

Note, to implement this patch some changes had to be made to the
wordpress TOSCA file as translation of certain pieces were not fully
supported, as described in bug #1440247. As a result of the change in
wordpress TOSCA file some existing test cases had to be skipped as
well. It is important to re-enable the skipped code and revert the
changes made to wordpress TOSCA file as part of bug #1440247 patch.

Also, shell scripts that support mysql, web server, and wordpress
installation and configuration were also updated to make sure the
HOT translation works with the ubuntu-software-config-os-init image.

To address bug #1447800 handling of null dictionaries was also
improved.

Change-Id: I2710eabb0a74c4d75498ac2d0fe3e50ea50133ab
Closes-Bug: #1435545
Closes-Bug: #1447800
Partial-Bug: #1436420
Related-Bug: #1440247

commit_message:
Replace pie chart with number for unlimited quotas

When quotas are unlimited hide the pie chart and replace with a number for
quickly glancing how much of 'x' is running

Change-Id: I3586323536ebbf330a4f5dc4529feed5e7987ec8
Closes-bug: 1435811

commit_message:
Read user project directly from request.user

User project should be read from request.user instead of
request.user.token.project.

Change-Id: Ic25d34c29698698b9a45fccf823a04dbf9f0b790

(1 comment)

It makes more sense to me to have the operating_system interface module at the bottom of the import stack. I suggest we move the module to trove/common/operating_system, move the execute_with_timeout function from utils into there, then switch to utils importing from operating_system.

This may be out of scope though. As is looks functional.'}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-03-13 15:46:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

@Matthew Thanks for the comment.

As mentioned below I intended this to be a sort of first-pass cleanup to the guestagent code with minimal impact on the existing implementations.
The guestagent, from its nature, makes this kind of system calls very often. I am not sure how valuable it would be for the rest of the trove.

Anyway, that would be a larger project with much broader impact possibly interacting with the oslo library stuff... certainly out of scope of this patch set.

This is more about centralizing most common (also wanted to do 'mv', 'rm', 'cp', and 'chown') shell commands to one place/module where they can be easily maintained and possibly moved around later.

:-)"}, {'account_id': 9782, 'date': '2015-03-18 20:02:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I believe operating_system is intended to be local to the guestagent.'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2015-03-21 10:06:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

if we're making a generic change_owner routine, I'd suggest a kwarg for timeout.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-13 00:18:48.000000000', 'message': 'Abstract 'mkdir' shell commands in guestagent

The guestagent commonly executes basic shell commands
such as 'mkdir' across multiple files and datastores.
Each datastore currently scripts its own shell calls.
Apart from cluttering the Python code with shell constructs,
it also makes maintenance of the shell calls more difficult by
requiring the same change be made across multiple lines,
source files and/or potentially even datastores.

The goal of this patch set is to provide a simple straightforward
interface for most common shell calls used across the guestagent
code while encapsulating the related shell code into a single module.

This patch set includes refactoring of 'mkdir' and related 'chown'
calls.
It also introduces unit tests ('guestagent/test_operating_system')
for the above implementations.

The shell code was moved into 'common/operating_system' module.
The replacing interface is:

def create_directory(dir_path, user=None, group=None, force=True):
    """Create a given directory as root and update its ownership
    (recursively) to the given user and group if any."""

The existing interface for 'chown' has been extended to maintain
consistency with 'mkdir'.

def update_owner(path, user, group, recursive=True, force=False):
    """Changes the owner and group of a given file.
    The call is a no-op if neither user nor group is provided."""

Most occurrences of the above two shell calls ('mkdir' and 'chown')
in the guestagent code have been replaced by the above abstraction.

Change-Id: I0fe96301087e3bd49d937c7c489006fd9d84ca1e
Closes-Bug: 1431618

'}, {'created': '2015-04-17 22:04:05.000000000', 'message': 'Abstract 'mkdir' shell commands in guestagent

The guestagent commonly executes basic shell commands
such as 'mkdir' across multiple files and datastores.
Each datastore currently scripts its own shell calls.
Apart from cluttering the Python code with shell constructs,
it also makes maintenance of the shell calls more difficult by
requiring the same change be made across multiple lines,
source files and/or potentially even datastores.

The goal of this patch set is to provide a simple straightforward
interface for most common shell calls used across the guestagent
code while encapsulating the related shell code into a single module.

This patch set includes refactoring of 'mkdir' and related 'chown'
calls.
It also introduces unit tests ('guestagent/test_operating_system')
for the above implementations.

The shell code was moved into 'common/operating_system' module.
The replacing interface is:

def create_directory(dir_path, user=None, group=None, force=True):
    """Create a given directory and update its ownership
    (recursively) to the given user and group if any."""

The existing interface for 'chown' has been extended to maintain
consistency with 'mkdir'.

def chown(path, user, group, recursive=True, force=False):
    """Changes the owner and group of a given file.
    """

The calls also take optional keyword arguments:
    :param as_root:          Execute as root.
    :type as_root:           boolean

    :param timeout:          Number of seconds if specified,
                             default if not.
                             There is no timeout if set to None.
    :type timeout:           integer

Most occurrences of the above two shell calls ('mkdir' and 'chown')
in the guestagent code have been replaced by the above abstraction.
I did not replace native Python os.chown() and os.mkdir() calls
and calls that are executed as a part of a larger shell script
in this patch set.

Change-Id: I0fe96301087e3bd49d937c7c489006fd9d84ca1e
Depends-On: Ib969a111d102b817c9f18437c1f36bd17e3a8a4b

commit_message:
Abstract 'mkdir' shell commands in guestagent

The guestagent commonly executes basic shell commands
such as 'mkdir' across multiple files and datastores.
Each datastore currently scripts its own shell calls.
Apart from cluttering the Python code with shell constructs,
it also makes maintenance of the shell calls more difficult by
requiring the same change be made across multiple lines,
source files and/or potentially even datastores.

The goal of this patch set is to provide a simple straightforward
interface for most common shell calls used across the guestagent
code while encapsulating the related shell code into a single module.

This patch set includes refactoring of 'mkdir' and related 'chown'
calls.
It also introduces unit tests ('guestagent/test_operating_system')
for the above implementations.

The shell code was moved into 'common/operating_system' module.
The replacing interface is:

def create_directory(dir_path, user=None, group=None, force=True):
    """Create a given directory and update its ownership
    (recursively) to the given user and group if any."""

The existing interface for 'chown' has been extended to maintain
consistency with 'mkdir'.

def chown(path, user, group, recursive=True, force=False):
    """Changes the owner and group of a given file.
    """

The calls also take optional keyword arguments:
    :param as_root:          Execute as root.
    :type as_root:           boolean

    :param timeout:          Number of seconds if specified,
                             default if not.
                             There is no timeout if set to None.
    :type timeout:           integer

Most occurrences of the above two shell calls ('mkdir' and 'chown')
in the guestagent code have been replaced by the above abstraction.
I did not replace native Python os.chown() and os.mkdir() calls
and calls that are executed as a part of a larger shell script
in this patch set.

Authored-By: Petr Malik <pmalik@tesora.com>
Change-Id: I0fe96301087e3bd49d937c7c489006fd9d84ca1e
Depends-On: Ib969a111d102b817c9f18437c1f36bd17e3a8a4b
Closes-Bug: 1431618
Related-Bug: 1438430

commit_message:
Don't return default for domain in v2 accessinfo

The V2 AccessInfo returns 'default' and 'Default' for domain_id and
domain_name parameters respectively because this information is not
included in the V2 token and it was trying to help.

Unfortunately this makes it impossible to tell if there is no domain
information available or the domain information is actually default
which may not be the case on all systems.

Make it so V2AccessInfo returns None for domain properties.

Change-Id: Ieb79c70ebe8e73b7f1a445015a3eb00bda322e8a

commit_message:
Libvirt: Correct logging information and progress when LM

Libvirt driver gives wrong progress information when doing live migration,
this case is happened when info.memory_total == 0, logging information will
log out 0% remaining, which should be 100% remaining.
This also impacts instance.progress.

Closes-Bug: #1441000
Change-Id: I392dcd4e0a8ecb8b19ec93db4629d799be2d1a4b

and the corresponding ports just to get the port ID. Then they were
calling get_ports again with those port IDs, resulting in two queries
to the port table when there should have only been one.

commit_message:
Remove double queries in l3 DB get methods

Two frequently called functions were querying the routerport table
and the corresponding ports just to get the port ID. Then they were
calling get_ports again with those port IDs, resulting in two queries
to the port table when there should have only been one.

This eliminates the second call to get_ports since all of the necessary
data hase been retrieved from the port table.

Change-Id: I806e9c380b7de048fe084b2baf4b6f92ab0edf6b
Partial-Bug: #1445412
(cherry picked from commit 3310c3c3d4c05c0d13f32f08f978ba4813e2a39a)

commit_message:
Remove double queries in l3 DB get methods

Two frequently called functions were querying the routerport table
and the corresponding ports just to get the port ID. Then they were
calling get_ports again with those port IDs, resulting in two queries
to the port table when there should have only been one.

This eliminates the second call to get_ports since all of the necessary
data hase been retrieved from the port table.

Change-Id: I806e9c380b7de048fe084b2baf4b6f92ab0edf6b
Partial-Bug: #1445412
(cherry picked from commit 3310c3c3d4c05c0d13f32f08f978ba4813e2a39a)

commit_message:
Set loading strategy to joined for Routerport/Port

The RouterPort model has a relationship to the ports model which
is frequently relied on to get the port IDs of interfaces attached
to a router. However, this defaults to the loading strategy to
'select', which meant a new query was being emitted for every
interface to the ports table just to get the ID.

This patch adjusts the relationship to be 'joined' by default so
one query will fetch the related ports.

Another option would have been not to use the port object at all since
the ID is all that the callers were usually interested in. However,
they would end up using the ID to do a port lookup, which is being
optimized away in another patch anyway so the full port object from
the relationship will end up getting used.

Change-Id: Id1ae35f845f7367d5f1f065c6fa637da7b980a2b
Partial-Bug: #1445412
(cherry picked from commit 10b17a884452736a6b214bcb7705b955192a1748)

is frequently relied on to get the port IDs of interfaces attached

the relationship will end up getting used.

commit_message:
Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for fixed_ip_get_*

This patches remove the hard-code permission checks for db call
fixed_ip_get_all and fixed_ip_get_all_by_host.

There are elevated contexts in the code used to call those calls
aren't removed in this patch. The elevated context will be cleaned up
in last step. This is safe if we forget removing some hard-code
permission.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

Change-Id: Ia1ad362e72d094c4ed755a46dec003d9c0d3725d

Add some tests for floating ips

* Associate floating ip to port that has already another floating ip
* Associate floating ip with port from another tenant

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-28 22:09:12.000000000', 'message': "Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: If8a132de65ba1e57ea93f98daac66816a3cefaa8

commit_message:
Finally let L3 and DHCP agents cleanup namespaces by default

There has been a problem with iproute package that resulted in errors
when deleting the namespaces, so deleting was turned off by default.
According to tests with iproute version 3.12.0 there is no such issue
so the option could be safely turned on by default.

DocImpact
Related-Bug: #1052535
Related-Bug: #1402739

Change-Id: I4c831f98fb2462382ef0f9216e265555186b965a

commit_message:
Adds force docker service start

Despite being started via upstart in rare cases docker service
wasn't available on VM first boot. This commit adds force
server star step

Closes-Bug: #1449510

commit_message:
Adds ability to delete docker applications from the host

Application deletion were supported on DSH/Pod but not exposed
in DockerApplication. Once it became exposed number of bugs in
KubernetesPod and DSH became visible.

Change-Id: I33650936a73994668f72348a909b7a51bae2b98c
Closes-Bug: #1446582

commit_message:
Execute pre/post deployment hooks on GC

Currently pre/post deployment are invoked only for
deployment (actions). Those hooks are used to stop
AgentListener. But they were not executed for GC
phase that could also start AgentListener.  As a result
we could get 2 AgentListeners running and stealing
messages from each other

Change-Id: If96db92e38f067bfed72cfc4a3d5619de2f0fad3
Closes-Bug: #1449500

[{'created': '2015-04-30 12:22:14.000000000', 'message': 'pselect exited on first exception

Due to eventlet bug in GreenPool implementation when first
spawned thread threw exception imap method exited immediately
without waiting for other spawned threads to accomplish.

Issue in eventlet github:
https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/issues/232

This commits wraps executed functions so that no exception can be
raised on imap boundary and then unwraps result after execution

 Closes-Bug: #1449497

Change-Id: I0e99de8e0711071c4a009e37a58ec22761e90e6c
'}]
commit_message:
pselect exited on first exception

Due to eventlet bug in GreenPool implementation when first
spawned thread threw exception imap method exited immediately
without waiting for other spawned threads to accomplish.

Issue in eventlet github:
https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/issues/232

This commits wraps executed functions so that no exception can be
raised on imap boundary and then unwraps result after execution

 Closes-Bug: #1449497

Change-Id: I0e99de8e0711071c4a009e37a58ec22761e90e6c

commit_message:
Don't update port with host id of None

In the L3 RPC code if the host for a port is not
present, it ends up calling update_port with the
host_id set to None. This does not update the host
id at all because it's treated as an unset attribute
which leads to the same thing happening on the next
iteration. These pointless update calls are expensive
because they involve a semaphore and calls to mechanism
drivers.

This patch adjusts the logic to only send a port
update if it actually has a host to ensure is on
the port.

Change-Id: Ic55496dd2ba3abcef0a2de9fc8699c391b79fa51
Partial-Bug: #1445412

This patch upgrades pyScss to 1.3.4 which fixes the stylesheet
ordering bug (which caused Bootstrap to be broken):

   https://github.com/Kronuz/pyScss/issues/274

To make this patch work, you will need to modify django-pyscss
once it is installed to fix this issue:

   https://github.com/fusionbox/django-pyscss/issues/34

Once upstream django-pyscss has been patched this will not be
necessary.

One issue with action-list.scss was discovered once the tools
were upgraded; I'm unsure whether this is an issue in the scss
or the tools (though the scss worked with the previous tool
version). I need someone with far greater experience with scss
to make the call there though, and possibly generate a bug
report / PR against upstream.

commit_message:
Upgrade pyScss to version 1.3.4

This patch upgrades pyScss to 1.3.4 which fixes the stylesheet
ordering bug (which caused Bootstrap to be broken):

   https://github.com/Kronuz/pyScss/issues/274

The change to action-list.scss which used to be part of this
patch has been moved to fix up global-requirements tempest in
change-id Idec7ce039b57476ce20b7b678431459c2ca0bdbf

Change-Id: I445cb5a97ee336d9f4a51a9808b88a38dd23dd4b
Closes-Bug: #1449789
Depends-On: I77d6f41fe7c9617298484969220f6fdfe82c3c36

commit_message:
Provide Fedora support for StrongSwan

The initial release of StrongSwan VPNaaS driver only support Ubuntu.
This patch will provide the Fedora support. The different usage of
StrongSwan between Fedora and Ubuntu are:
- Uses 'strongswan' CLI command instead of 'ipsec'
- Configuration files location is different
- Strongswan.d directory in template directory does not include
  'charon' directory

Change-Id: I27d8518d1d8110453d4674a0c6fb3cb6072a32f0
Closes-bug: 1444776
Closes-bug: 1441788

commit_message:
Determine CentOS 6 platform in cache-devstack

The centos element (which is CentOS 6.x specific) doesn't provide
DIB_RELEASE so we have to identify it another way.

Change-Id: Ibf3b25b99f03c6077538dec6c3770dc0f690e3f5

Add support for NFS Backup

Adds support for configuring Cinder to backup volumes to an NFS
share.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-17 23:43:21.000000000', 'message': '(WIP) Making changes so that custom LP flow works in devstack

In order to test this you will need:
- latest nova-docker code
- set image_storage=glance in /etc/solum/solum.conf
- set scheduler_default_filters = AllHostsFilter in
  /etc/nova/nova.conf
- have an app that listens to the same port that is specified
  in the basic.yaml heat template.

  Sample app repo:
  https://github.com/devdattakulkarni/solum-python-sample-app

  Notice that the app.py listens on port 7035 and
  the default port in basic.yaml is 7035

  TODO: Set the default port in the heat template to
  the port that is specified by the user at the time of
  app creation

Change-Id: I48a247c47ca508a698335133b61706bc89f8d150
'}, {'created': '2015-04-20 19:49:12.000000000', 'message': '(WIP) Making changes so that custom LP flow works in devstack

In order to test this you will need:
- latest nova-docker code
- set image_storage=glance in /etc/solum/solum.conf
- set scheduler_default_filters = AllHostsFilter in

commit_message:
Add image show tests

Image v2 uses warlock objects rather than the usua Resource objects
so we need to test for those.  This adds a subset of the Image v2
schema that should be enough to test for proper warlock image handling.

Depends-On: Ic95db2f63d9f5f37e29f0d7e048397da311fbf8c
Change-Id: Ib89cce87f110a554f40e726718e31d39b500a6ae

Drop auth and corresponding unit tests

Fix all auth imports to use tempest-lib. Drop auth and related
unit tests.
Use token client from tempest-lib as well.

The POST request is the only one implemented differently (nova uses it for updating multiple properties at once, this proposal defines it as a more traditional "create a single resource").'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2014-12-22 15:23:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1063, 'date': '2014-12-23 21:18:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

(2 comments)

Ed, I replied to your points inline.'}, {'account_id': 10559, 'date': '2015-01-21 16:43:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-01-27 23:40:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

I have some serious concerns about the current proposal. It's a massive change from the way Swift currently operates, and I think it also leaves out crucial guidelines.

URL munging (adding /metadata) is incompatible with URLs that are user-chosen (eg object storage). This is the same with the URL references to individual keys.

There is no way to set data and metadata at the same time, since creation of metadata is defined as a POST with a defined body.

Swift solves both of the above issues today by setting metadata in request headers on the object PUT creation request or updating the metadata with request headers in a POST to the existing object. This allows data and metadata to be set at the same time.

There is no mention of support for If-*Match conditional requests and how they should be supported. This is neccessary to ameliorate concerns about partial updates of metadata in a distributed environment handling concurrent requests.

There is no description of privileged, system, internal, or otherwise filtered metadata and how that should be addressed. See the sys-meta concept in Swift, which allows for internal/admin information to be set on entities in the cluster. (See http://docs.openstack.org/developer/swift/development_middleware.html#sysmeta and linked documents.)"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-01-30 11:02:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

I don't think we should be in the business of specifying resources and the details of their identity or representation, as I commented[1] in the meeting last night.

It's certainly okay that we make suggestions that are non-binding about types of resources in certain contexts but they should be prefaced with caveats and be explicit about the context where the _guidelines_ are useful. Something like:

If your API will be used in a way where a separate metadata resource will be useful (<include examples of such>) one way to do this that might be useful is described below...blah blah etc.

[1] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/api_wg/2015/api_wg.2015-01-29-16.00.log.html#l-192"}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-02-02 18:42:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-02-02 18:43:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Added description of how to access metadata together with other properties of the parent resource, per Ryan Brown suggestion.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-02 18:50:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-api-wg-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/29/141229/7/check/gate-api-wg-docs/dcd5a6a//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 37s
- gate-api-wg-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/29/141229/7/check/gate-api-wg-python27/279e62e/ : SUCCESS in 1m 26s'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-02-02 19:09:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

John, sorry it took me so long to reply to your review.

> There is no way to set data and metadata at the same time

True. I have updated the spec now to include the metadata as a field in the representation of the parent resource.

I open to be convinced otherwise, but I feel request headers are not the best way to represent metadata. Handling of character encodings is awkward in headers, and it is also unclear to me how HTTP caching works for header data. Also, you typically compute etags from the body, so metadata would not be part of it.

> There is no mention of support for If-*Match conditional requests and how they should be supported
There is nothing special about conditional requests pertaining to metadata. You are free to generate etags for the bodies of these metadata requests, and implement conditionals according to the HTTP spec.

> There is no description of privileged, system, internal, or otherwise filtered metadata
Correct. This was not something I considered. The way I implemented this type of thing in the past (non OpenStack projects) was to provide different resource representations according to the role of the user that is making the request, so users only see the metadata they are allowed to see. I honestly feel it is outside of the scope of this spec.

I hope you understand that it is really impossible to write a spec that agrees with all the implementations of metadata that we have in OpenStack APIs. I believe this is a pretty standard implementation that agrees with REST principles.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-02-03 01:29:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

I still don't like the metadata being treated as something discrete from the resource itself. I don't think that works well for object storage (or likely and data-plane API).

But, assuming we go down this path (two documents), here's an alternate suggestion:

Instead of using a json-encoded body, what about using multi-part mime documents? That allows separate headers on each document and streaming of the body of each document.

---

Another comment on a different point: json keys and url paths are used interchangeably in this document. Please set some keys as non-ASCII (eg right-to-left arabic would be good) and show how that translates into the URL path. Or define the guidelines as excluding that."}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-02-03 15:24:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

> I still don't like the metadata being treated as something discrete from the resource itself. I don't think that works well for object storage (or likely and data-plane API).

Can you describe why you don't think it works well? What's the reasoning for it not working well? Have you read the recent discussions about how these guidelines are meant to be used? [1] [2]

> But, assuming we go down this path (two documents), here's an alternate suggestion:  
>  
> Instead of using a json-encoded body, what about using multi-part mime documents? That allows separate headers on each document and streaming of the body of each document.

I'm not certain how familiar you are with the relevant RFCs. I'm very familiar. All headers, whether they be in the HTTP headers or per-request headers have to be latin-1 encoded. And if you want to use non-latin-1 characters, you have to follow RFC 2231 [3] which pretty much no one does (except for Django). And that's just for MIME headers. There are similar (more recent) RFCs for handling them in HTTP headers, but given that 2231 is over 10 years old at this point, and the newer ones are much much younger, I'll let you guess at the odds of any framework handling it properly. And until there's an oslo.wsgi, I don't think any single OpenStack project should really bother handling them itself when JSON just works out of the box.


> Another comment on a different point: json keys and url paths are used interchangeably in this document. Please set some keys as non-ASCII (eg right-to-left arabic would be good) and show how that translates into the URL path. Or define the guidelines as excluding that.

Encoding non-ASCII into URIs is actually trivial. The relevant RFCs are all clear about how they're supposed to work depending on the part of the URI they're in. For example, schemes and authorities can only have ASCII characters. If an authority has non-ASCII characters, it's an IRI and has strict rules to become a URI. non-ASCII in paths, queries, and fragments are all allowable. It's up to WSGI to apache/python/wsgi to support it at that point. Given that Flask supports unicode like that (see httpbin, for a working example) it would seem to me that python/wsgi at least support it.

So again, I'm not really certain what your concern is here. If you want more specific RFC citations, please let me know. I do this all the time.

[1]: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-January/055694.html
[2]: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-February/055763.html
[3]: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2231"}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-02-03 15:38:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

It seems I forgot to link RFC 2231 above: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2231'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-02-04 00:36:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I'd only like some examples in the guideline about how to do the key/value encoding. I think including examples of "non-standard" data would be very helpful to myself and others trying to implement these guidelines. If there are specific RFCs that define how something should be treated, including references would be helpful too.

I do have two concerns, still. First is that the entire data and metadata is serialized in the same document. The data of Swift objects is arbitrarily large, so putting that into a json object (or even trying to serialize it) is tricky, to say the least.

The second is that the /metadata* suffix isn't compatible with any system that has used user-defined URLs to reference things. Is there any way to alternatively reference metadata without breaking read/write access to existing resources with the new API?'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-02-04 01:06:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

John, not sure if I understand. Are you asking about how to use non-latin characters in the JSON bodies of requests and responses? There is a standard procedure in HTTP to do this, you specify the encoding used in the body in the content type header (RFC 2045 I think, Ian will not miss the opportunity to correct me if I'm wrong).

Regarding the first of your two concerns, for Swift I don't think it would be a good idea to wrap the object data in JSON. What I would do for your case is to return the data like you do now, but without the metadata headers. Then you have the proposed "/metadata" request for the metadata. (I know you don't like the /metadata suffix, but let's assume we find a way to agree on that).

Now, regarding the /metadata suffix, I think the very dynamic format of the Swift URLs does not lend to adding suffixes. What I would do if I had to implement URLs that have accounts/containers/objects in them is to use more traditional /<resource_type>/<resource_id> structure. For example:

/accounts/{account_id}
/containers/{account_id}/{container_id}
/objects/{account_id}/{container_id}/{object_id}

With this URL structure the number of components is known in advance based on the prefix component, so then you can add /metadata at the end without ambiguity.'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-02-04 16:13:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

So specifying a charset for anything returning application/json is wrong (e.g., ``Content-Type: application/json; charset=latin-1``, is wrong). [1]

That aside, I agree with Miguel that Swift's resource scheme could use some work. For those who are viewing this in Gerrit, it'll be easier to read like this:

    /accounts{/account_id}
    /containers{/account_id}{/container_id}
    /objects{/account_id}{/container_id}{/object_id}

I think that would nicely allow for

    /accounts/{account_id}/metadata
    /containers/{account_id}/{container_id}/metadata
    /objects/{account_id}/{container_id}/{object_id}/metadata

That seems to be orthogonal to the benefits or problems associated with this guideline though given that this seems to be a problem specific to swift.

As for specifying the encoding of the metadata response, in this Guideline, that also seems to tip on the side of more information than is necessary. A separate guideline can be proposed that very sternly suggests following RFC 4627 when returning JSON response bodies, including following the Content-Type definitions and not including a charset parameter. I'd like to stress that guideline would be a separate change.

[1] If you look at Section 6 of RFC 4627 (which defines application/json) (http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc4627#section-6) you'll see that there are no parameters it accepts. Further, JSON is specified in Section 3 of the same RFC (http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc4627#section-3) to be specifically one of UTF-8, UTF-16, or UTF-32. The first 4 octets of the response body will indicate which it is (and will also indicate endian-ness)."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-02-04 19:17:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

Quoting:

    /objects/{account_id}/{container_id}/{object_id}/metadata

This still won't work, as Swift object names may contain slashes. Even if we did throw backwards compatibility out the window and do something like this, we'd still have ambiguity between "the object named testruns/1379/matches/metadata" and "metadata for the object named testruns/1379/matches".'}, {'account_id': 12807, 'date': '2015-02-04 19:43:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

This seems to have gotten slightly off track.

At no point have I seen or heard the API Working Group members taking the position that the recommendations are binding on new APIs or endpoints or require remediation of existing APIs within any existing projects.

If that needs to be put on the next meeting agenda again, or if the language already accepted on that point needs to be revisited, let's do that.

This review was originally about what, if any, general guidance makes sense for metadata (not specifically for a data plane, nor for a specific data plane)."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-03-09 21:08:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(8 comments)

Thanks, Miguel, a few suggestions inline :)

Best,

-jay'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-03-09 22:56:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Jay, thanks for the feedback. I explained why I used these representation formats inline. If this seems too wordy then I can switch to more concise formats such as the ones you suggested. But I think the formats that I picked are more future-proof.'}, {'account_id': 10670, 'date': '2015-03-10 16:21:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

I think this is coming together well but I'm not feeling quite right about saying +1 (even assuming the changes suggested thus far are made). The reason is because it feels very weird to me to be making the assumption that tags are a universal enough concept to be describing a guideline that we hope everyone will follow. I would feel more comfortable with something in the introduction that is a good deal more explicit about what these tags are and how they are expected to mean. Yes, you've already said that they are meant to be used as ways of distinguishing and filtering collections of stuff, so that's good but it may be wise to identify those types of resources which are receptive to that kind of attribution. A single entity of some sort which is going to be selected into some set for some kind of purpose is what we usually think of. What about a collection? Can a collection have tags? Should it?"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-02-16 19:06:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Soft -1 on this, only because of the use of comma-delimited parameters vs. just using multiple query params like:

 tag-any=this&tag-any=that

I don't know of any client or server HTTP frameworks that don't support the HTTP standard of multiple query parameters...

That said, it's not the end of the world, and if the world wants to go with this, I'll chat with Sergey about re-working the Nova tags API to match (it's actually still in the final patch review, so is possible to do it.

-jay"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-02-23 20:52:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

++ to what Chris said. :)'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-02-24 15:23:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

De facto standards are great until a new (RFC) standard has been accepted that makes them inherently incorrect (like 6570). We as a community started moving towards JSON Home, which (while itself not an RFC because it was allowed to expire) mandates the use of URI Templates (RFC 6570). So either we need to drop the use of templates+JSON Home altogether (which I don't see any of the projects doing) or write guidelines to make complying with JSON Home + URI Templates easier. This guideline does the latter."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-02-24 15:34:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I'm not really following the point you're trying to make Ian. Could you perhaps make it more explicitly?

I thought at first you were trying to say "we can't do it that way because of URI-templates" but from what I can tell URI-templates are pretty clear about multiple query parameters. Multiple tag params would be:

    {?tag*}

Help me out please.'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-02-24 17:11:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 12807, 'date': '2015-02-24 17:13:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-02-24 17:23:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Ian, you're really confusing me with this: "we ever use URI Templates (RFC 6570), then repeated query parameters aren't supported there"

* https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6570#section-3.2.8 shows {?tag*}
* the python uritemplate package (written by two of the authors of the RFC) supports it too:

    >>> from uritemplate import expand
    >>> expand("http://www.example.com/api{?tag*}", {"tag": ["one", "two", "three"]})
    'http://www.example.com/api?tag=one&tag=two&tag=three'

It's fine if we don't want to use it if we can demonstrate that important and common libraries don't support it, but if you're going to point at the RFC please be clear about what you are trying to say and get it right!'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-02-24 18:31:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I think an important question that hasn't been asked is why some of you feel that this:

    http://example.com/?tag=red&tag=blue

is better than this:

    http://example.com/?tags=red,blue

As I mentioned before, we had this discussion before, for the sorting spec by Steven Kaufer. Back then we agreed that not repeating args is better. Are we now wanting to change that decision?"}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2015-02-24 18:51:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Added SSL parameter for nova to talk with secured glance

After https://review.openstack.org/#/c/72974 nova (somehow?)
uses ssl/cert_file to connect to glance. Analysis of such
behavior reasons is out of scope of this CR.

This change fixes configuration parameters according to
current nova behavior.

Change-Id: Ib78878af37484f3e176c9b5d27d188aa35a79924
Closes-Bug: #1405484

commit_message:
AccessInfo is not a dict

Remove the dict subclass from AccessInfo and make it take a full token
object. This means that the object we are passed is a real token, and
not something that's been messed with.

We may need to add dict accessors back later but strip it out for now.

Change-Id: Ie9f134efeae91cfc8044fe97cfab066c84d07d50

commit_message:
Make ServiceCatalog take an actual catalog

The input for creating a service catalog should be a catalog dictionary,
not the AccessInfo object.

Add a helper function for loading a catalog from token data. This makes
the interaction unusual in AccessInfo but will help later.

Change-Id: Idf0ea38941b5270d4166db5661428c0ed2bd040e

commit_message:
Provide lsb_release in snapshot builds

Some CentOS 6 images do not come with redhat-lsb-core preinstalled,
so the lsb_release command is not available when prepare_node.sh
wants it. Make sure we install it first if it's not already there.

Change-Id: Ieeae21538c237e069acbc4df051474071b81ba4a

commit_message:
Update tempest and AIO to test cinder backups

This commit allows tempest to be configured to test the cinder backup
service.

Additionally, we:
- add a new function to openstack_tempest_gate.sh so we can include
  some cinder-backup-related API tests in our test list
- update bootstrap-aio.sh to enable cinder backups and the ability to
  test cinder backups
- update run-tempest.sh to include the cinder backup tests in the
  default test list

Change-Id: Iee7b40c9640aad6613b56a0f033da4294f3bfce7
Closes-Bug: #1449427

commit_message:
Remove extra requirements

Remove ipaddr and simpledispatch as they are dependencies pulled
in by WSME and pecan.

Since these requirements are not part of global-requirements a
build error will occur with devstack attempting to sync the requirements
that can be prevented by removing requirements that should be
pulled in by other packages.

Change-Id: Ib83afb4f11e478764f80a2fa8c0f47903ff999a2

commit_message:
Add basic orchestration tests to the gate check

This change adds a "heat_api" test list that includes a few
basic orchestration api tests. To make it easier to build test
sets, the openstack_tempest_gate.sh script now accepts
multiple test lists as arguments, which are combined into a
single master list. The default test set for the gate check now
includes the "scenario" and "heat_api" lists.

Conflicts:
	rpc_deployment/roles/tempest/files/rpc_tempest_gate.sh
	scripts/run-tempest.sh

Change-Id: I51d5a7c47c3b5ff6a12f7ebccb0f40afa571c3d0
(cherry picked from commit 724ad211727b136d9f149fed75da4e5dc7206070)

commit_message:
devstack: Run ovn-controller with sudo.

ovn-controller needs root access to be able to manage the local
switch.  Without it we get errors like:

...|WARN|unix:/usr/local/var/run/openvswitch/br-int.mgmt:
connection failed (Permission denied)

Change-Id: I3d260f747ffe8adceed2dec3f0354c0870009a9f

commit_message:
devstack: Update integration bridge config

Update configuration of the integration bridge with settings
recommended for OVN:

    fail-mode=secure other-config:disable-in-band=true

For more info about these recommendations, see:

    http://openvswitch.org/pipermail/dev/2015-April/054863.html

Change-Id: I2d07fbf57f48cb6de26ccff85693eb3d0b7107e5

commit_message:
Bump tempest-lib min version

The new version of tempest-lib was just pushed out. Tempest (and
likely other projects too) will start leveraging new functionality
added in this release, however before that can be done the min
version needs to be updated. For example, see tempest change:
I8c2772d9fb42d352f4a1d3e74e20ce6e8f483559 where the new version
is required.

Change-Id: Ie6435b4f3a367b0a8cec68f21c0b4f5f61d6b688

commit_message:
relax final pins

The following packages were pinned to a specific version, however they
are not the kind of software that should be pinned (they aren't
linters). Being non linters means we should either work with a range,
or we should remove them from being a dependency because they have
terrible compatibility stories.

Change-Id: I62f6ab9c34300482256b34456bb1b133d8fc45b3

commit_message:
Default glance swift_backend to use local swift

The default values should use the local swift installation, since these
are only used when the glance backend is set to "swift" it won't matter
if there is no local swift when the backend is set to "file".

Adjust AIO script to use the defaults.

Move the configuration values from user_secrets.yml into
user_variables.yml since these are not passwords that should be set.
Additionally comment them out by default.

Change-Id: I579500a0287bc29f27fdbdb4f810212a2e194dea
Closes-Bug: #1450117

This particular problem seemed to show up because Murano and Heat (possibly b/c of Keystone) use incompatible versions of some package.  If they truly require incompatible versions, this isn't something to fix in Congress--it's a basic incompatibility of the software services.  At least that's how I understood it.  What I think we should do is whatever devstack does for requirements.txt."}, {'account_id': 14795, 'date': '2015-04-29 22:51:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Except for tox, 'pip install -U' is rarely used.  For the thirdparty-requirements.txt, I think it makes sense to remove the -U because we don't want to upgrade dependencies if they are already satisfied.  It may cause version restriction as we see in the case of Heat.  I don't see the down side of removing -U in this case."}, {'account_id': 14265, 'date': '2015-04-30 08:18:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

[{'created': '2015-04-29 21:35:54.000000000', 'message': 'Fix stevedore package conflict in devstack script

When installing python-muranoclient during devstack setup,
the dependent package stevedore is upgraded to 1.4.0 and it
conflicts with versions specified in global-requirements
causing heat failure. This change removes the "-U" from
"pip install" to skip installing a package if it exists
(as in the case of stevedore=1.3.0).

Closes-Bug: #1450010
Change-Id: Ia0fe33d66f7012391d54e28a804eb7540de323d4
'}]
commit_message:
Fix stevedore package conflict in devstack script

When installing python-muranoclient during devstack setup,
the dependent package stevedore is upgraded to 1.4.0 and it
conflicts with versions specified in global-requirements
causing heat failure. This change removes the "-U" from
"pip install" to skip installing a package if it exists
(as in the case of stevedore=1.3.0).

Closes-Bug: #1450010
Change-Id: Ia0fe33d66f7012391d54e28a804eb7540de323d4

commit_message:
Lock down PBR to < version 0.11.0

This change was made to ensure that PBR is using version < 0.11.0.
This is because changes in upstream PBR have made it impossible to
build contributing packages in heat and will likely impact other
services until the switch to liberty is in full effect. To ensure
consistent building of OpenStack packages PBR is now being installed
in the repo server containers which will ensure there are no
assumptions being made when creating python packages from OpenStack
contributing sources that may not be as well maintained as others.

Change-Id: I20c216543e63ef142119c2625fb219e030a708dd
Partial-bug: 1450733

I'd rather see meaningful log messages what was actually blocked by policy.

commit_message:
Add logging when policies forbid an action

There is currently no logging in images.py of glance API v1 or v2
and other files of glance API when policies forbid an action.This
patch adds logging in these situations.

Co-Authored-By: Ian Cordasco <ian.cordasco@rackspace.com>
Co-Authored-By: Kamil Rykowski <kamil.rykowski@intel.com>

Closes-Bug: #1270229
Change-Id: I32afbfc98a3de6370b0396f39c2cf481f6fc47a9

commit_message:
Remove the factory from service catalog

This should always be accessed via an AccessInfo, and the AccessInfo
already knows what version the token is so it should never need a
factory.

commit_message:
Updated cinder rootwrap for juno based on upstream

This change re-bases the cinder rootwrap volume filters based on
what is upstream. These changes should fix issues with cinder DD
that have been apparent in earlier versions of Juno.

Change-Id: I5a6af1b9d61e3bbb8e85c79ff55a91648a73e5e4
Closes-Bug: 1444602

commit_message:
Don't save version into the dictionary

By adding version to the dictionary you are getting further away from
the standard token object.

People do use this version property for figuring out what token version
it is so move it to a class property as it should never change anyway.

Change-Id: I3153b364248bf43d445ad2044f0c896efab6e573

commit_message:
Updated ldap config to support multi domain

Enables default domain support using ldap. This change moves the
ldap config to the default domain and enables domain specific
drivers.

Change-Id: I781c0f266e7a6797e8e2ea0bfc7d28254335d5e3
Closes-Bug: #1447768

commit_message:
Hyperv agent does not respect remoteIpPrefix

Fixes Hyperv issue where Hyperv agent does not respect the remoteIp prefix
specified as part of security group rules.
Hyperv Neutron agent always takes 0.0.0.0/0 as the remote Ip address by
default which is now fixed so that we will be able to specify
more restrictive security group rules using remoteIp prefix.

Closes-Bug: #1443862

Change-Id: I497aea5d803bba69f52eef19c0f9c743e678e6d7

[{'created': '2015-04-30 14:05:19.000000000', 'message': 'Lower default backup_metadata_version to 1

Kilo cinder supports both version 1 and 2, however juno cinder only
supports version 1.  Running
tempest.api.volume.admin.test_volumes_backup against a juno cinder
installation w/ backup_metadata_version set to 2 results in the
following cinder-backup error being logged:

BackupOperationError: Metadata restore failed due to incompatible
                      version

Partial-bug: #1399386
Change-Id: I20852c5fb331d9cbd297ecbd60a2b57d4fa37266
'}]
commit_message:
Lower default backup_metadata_version to 1

Kilo cinder supports both version 1 and 2, however juno cinder only
supports version 1.  Running
tempest.api.volume.admin.test_volumes_backup against a juno cinder
installation w/ backup_metadata_version set to 2 results in the
following cinder-backup error being logged:

BackupOperationError: Metadata restore failed due to incompatible
                      version

Partial-bug: #1399386
Change-Id: I20852c5fb331d9cbd297ecbd60a2b57d4fa37266

Formerly, the error message for an unreadable Heat template was always
the same, regardless of why it was unreadable; the original error was
simply discarded. This includes the original error in the exception
that is reraised from _get_template_from_file() so that the end user

'}]
commit_message:
Improve error message from unreadable Heat template

Formerly, the error message for an unreadable Heat template was always
the same, regardless of why it was unreadable; the original error was
simply discarded. This includes the original error in the exception
that is reraised from _get_template_from_file() so that the end user
might have a better idea of what the problem is.

Change-Id: Ic5e773ca1dd49c707c848cfe1dc6163e9bceb228

commit_message:
Move TODO out of published docs.

https://readthedocs.org/projects/networking-ovn/.  The TODO list seems
like something that doesn't need to be included there, so just keep it
in a standalone file.

commit_message:
Change auth_token to use keystoneclient

The auth_token middleware should use keystoneclient for all its
communication with keystone.

bp auth-token-use-client

Depends-On: If802e8a47e45ae00112de3739334b4b5482d0500
Change-Id: Ib6ff5b0d9b260d03fe5d120fa47035886f43439c

commit_message:
Fixes tests to use the config fixture

Tests should not be altering the global config object. Instead they
should be using the fixture so that state is properly restarted after a
test run.

Change-Id: I0d37a3f7e4e8dc3074be7721de6befed7e094c41

commit_message:
Change file loading mechanism for heat tests

Improve file loading mechanism for heat tests. Previously,
heat tests loaded template files for every tests. "types.set"
allows to exclude redundant file operations from tests.
In addition, the unit tests for heat rally-scenarios were updated
and mocking of CONF.benchmark was excluded from unit-tests.

Change-Id: Ibdace7bf96ff822701ee8505f1dcd232999a6fe8

commit_message:
Support size range in Cinder create_volume and extend_volume

It is useful for some test cases to set up volume size from some
range, not only specific value. This change add such possibility
to create_volume and extend_volume.

Change-Id: Ic7cc9270eb8d31dcbe3d30acf6f24cf9c41a6fd1

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I5bd1cdc35d2ecaf98a0802fff589d8c37aaa8028

commit_message:
add image smoke tags

This adds smoke tag to basic operations around glance v2 api (create,
get, update, delete) for images. This is needed because the only image
tests previously in the smoke tag were compute image proxy calls.

Change-Id: I1914437b1eda54f58bc21c5bbd4f18877748a665

commit_message:
Fix missing default value for JSCS var in run_tests.sh

Adds default value so ./run_tests.sh without --jscs doesn't produce warning.

commit_message:
Removed metadata from the nova service list.

The metadata service is now handled by it's own service
(openstack-nova-metadata-api) and thus does not need to
be included in the main nova-api process.

This resolves occasional race condition where
openstack-nova-metadata-api starts before
openstack-nova-api and prevents the nova api from
starting.

Change-Id: Ie665593aaffecdf43008489f21f3e4ab55e985f8

commit_message:
Removed tempest git entry

The tempest role has an entry within the defaults of the role and
it could cause confusion when dealing with tempest as the main
package version is being specified in
`vars/repo_packages/openstack_services.yml`. Being that these
variables are no longer used they have been removed.

Implements blueprint: master-kilofication
(cherry picked from commit bddfa51fce403d84dd9a2ae9f9fa1baf7f582dbc)


Change-Id: I197afac1ce50d9bad778dda5cc4a23a0821fceeb

commit_message:
Revert state if attachment already exists

When attach is called twice for the same volume and instance the
attach_volume checks if the attachment already exists and returns.
This leaves the volume in 'Attaching' state. The volume status should
be reset to 'in-use' if we see the attachment already exists.

Change-Id: I2a2d28de59af234300082ab4655b0bc10699d54c
Closes-Bug: #1449980
(cherry picked from commit 709949d904c7f1d0e13b41bf6723d71bcf6b5652)

[{'created': '2015-04-30 21:34:50.000000000', 'message': "Fix assert on call count for encodeutils.safe_decode mock

Commit c084b9d57ce8def5a20159364c16290ad67ad0a5 added a global call to
encodeutils.safe_decode in oslo.log 1.1.0 which can mess up the strict
call_count check on the mock in this test.

This prevents nova from updating requirements.txt to use oslo.log >=
1.1.0 so we have to change the test to be less restrictive about the
mock call count here.

We just check the calls to the mock and make sure that at least two
calls were made where the errors='ignore' kwarg was passed, which is
what _create_domain does.

Change-Id: I68d41c2713ad558112c35e4a35af39a4ef3bdec6
"}]
commit_message:
Fix assert on call count for encodeutils.safe_decode mock

Commit c084b9d57ce8def5a20159364c16290ad67ad0a5 added a global call to
encodeutils.safe_decode in oslo.log 1.1.0 which can mess up the strict
call_count check on the mock in this test.

This prevents nova from updating requirements.txt to use oslo.log >=
1.1.0 so we have to change the test to be less restrictive about the
mock call count here.

We just check the calls to the mock and make sure that at least two
calls were made where the errors='ignore' kwarg was passed, which is
what _create_domain does.

Change-Id: I68d41c2713ad558112c35e4a35af39a4ef3bdec6

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: Ifa8baab33cdb3e606cf175a8c29c3a4ef6c44480
