commit_message:
Update Backup and Restore section for NFS driver

Kilo adds support for use of an NFS exported backup repository
alongside Swift, Ceph, and TSM.

This update provides information in the Backup and Restore section
of the Cinder chapter of the Administrator's Guide on configuration
settings for the NFS backup driver.

Change-Id: I7754e640dd5d33e9c7afc664d4dbc5e4fddde7a7

commit_message:
Make test_version_string_with_package_is_good work with pbr 0.11

nova.version uses the version_string() API not version. Fix the test to
reflect that and make it work with pbr 0.11

Closes-Bug: #1450682
Change-Id: I4887b8000c9943c91f8add56fcc54fa18e78d683

commit_message:
Update self with db result in InstanceInfoCache.save

The InstanceInfoCache save method calls db.instance_info_cache_update
to update the database and receives an updated sqlalchemy model as a
return value. However, the result isn't saved to the self.fields of
the InstanceInfoCache object, though it is sent to update cells,
which is inconsistent. It doesn't seem critical as we expect to
receive mostly the same data back from the database as we already
have, except for the "created_at" and "updated_at" fields.

Change-Id: I64be855a194990f898ce4e572f42975a07bf1d3c

commit_message:
Make test_version_string_with_package_is_good work with pbr 0.11

nova.version uses the version_string() API not version. Fix the test to
reflect that and make it work with pbr 0.11

Closes-Bug: #1450682
Change-Id: I4887b8000c9943c91f8add56fcc54fa18e78d683

commit_message:
Decrease PO files for python projects

Remove untranslated strings and location information from PO files. The
location information is still in the POT files as reference for easy
regeneration using "msgmerge POTFILE POFILE -o COMPLETEPOFILE".

This moves the git add command to the end since compress_po_files
changes the files.

Change-Id: I8d9f80276085ffe4dd614960457637330ca28370

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-01 12:39:08.000000000', 'message': 'Always call hdisk removal from vscsi volume driver

This change updates the vscsi volume driver to ensure that the hdisk
removal is always invoked.  The hdisk removal significantly speeds up
subsequent discoveries.  The changes to pypowervm should remove risks
from running the API.

The change is done so that an error from the hdisk job does not block
volume disconnect.  The volume will have already been disconnected from
the VM by the time the command is run.  If the hdisk remove fails for
some reason, a subsequent attach should clean it up (but can be slower
when it does so).

Change-Id: Ib823f793ec4b951111301286743c6bd243b863fe
'}]
commit_message:
Always call hdisk removal from vscsi volume driver

This change updates the vscsi volume driver to ensure that the hdisk
removal is always invoked.  The hdisk removal significantly speeds up
subsequent discoveries.  The changes to pypowervm should remove risks
from running the API.

The change is done so that an error from the hdisk job does not block
volume disconnect.  The volume will have already been disconnected from
the VM by the time the command is run.  If the hdisk remove fails for
some reason, a subsequent attach should clean it up (but can be slower
when it does so).

Change-Id: Ib823f793ec4b951111301286743c6bd243b863fe

commit_message:
Fix pbr and it's version checks (unblock gates)

New version of pbr 0.11 was released and it checks
that version in setup.cfg is bigger then latest tag

To avoid future issues we will let pbr calulate version
instead of hardcode them in setup.cfg

Temporary disable coverage job to merge this patch

Partial-bug: #1450731

Change-Id: I0c00c231cea1a0506107133803406eb56694f690

commit_message:
remove XML middleware from default paste config

While this patch removes the xml_body middleware from the default paste
pipeline (thus failing against tempest tests which expect it), it
preserves support and functional test coverage for that middleware.

This is a softer step toward https://review.openstack.org/#/c/125738/

Change-Id: Ibd8020967ea89e6c8c8a55073e658f180faf1c00
Closes-Bug: 1384382
Closes-Bug: 1384789
Blueprint: removed-as-of-kilo

Gordon, please see the original bug in https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo/+bug/1338732.  The problem is the producer may reconnect before the consumer declares the queue, and in case the consumer never comes back, the producer should time out.  What other strategy can you suggest to fix this?'}, {'account_id': 8784, 'date': '2014-08-20 08:19:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Personally I would have the request resent on timeout (or have options to control that), rather than trying to make the request and response both completely reliable. Since publish is unconfirmed, you can always lose messages on failover anyway.

However, if a 'tactical' fix is wanted for the particular symptoms around the loss of the response queue, then I think a short ttl (x-expires) on response queues (see https://review.openstack.org/110058), and having the durability of the response queue match the durability of the request queue would be better. (This is a suggestion on a workaround for the symptoms reported however, rather than what I personally believe to be the right solution. To me, replicating or persisting all responses is not sensible and leads to poor scalability. The request-response pattern can happily tolerate the request or response being unreliable, by simply retrying the whole request.)"}, {'account_id': 7536, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:39:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

Maybe, resent request on timeout, it is better idea than incessantly request during 5 minutes. Check response, and choose to stop or continue accordingly to a response. If I correctly understood Gordon's recommendation, my tip is something similar."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-09-06 11:52:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Workflow-1

Unfortunately, since we're in the feature and string freeze period for Juno, we can't add a new configuration option. I'll look at this more closely next week to see if I can suggest a way to have the fix without adding an option."}, {'account_id': 10234, 'date': '2014-09-07 19:26:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8772, 'date': '2014-09-11 22:44:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

commit_message:
Publishers will eventually time out if consumer never reconnects

If a client dies after sending a request to the server, the server may
loop forever retrying to deliver the reply.

Added config rabbit_publish_timeout defaults to 0 sec, no timeout at all.

Change-Id: Id7fb72f88be675d17f47c958c32d1055f967b820

commit_message:
Hyper-V: checks for existent Notes in list_instance_notes

If there are VMs with Notes = None, the Hyper-V Driver cannot
start, as it tries to iterate over None, which results in an
exception.

This commit adds a check if the Notes exist, before iterating over
them.

Closes-Bug: #1438638

Change-Id: Icebdc03d7249fdf903b94b2f61f4891f5c9d6e50

No problem.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-04-13 21:33:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-04-13 22:33:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(6 comments)

I have some strong thoughts, but only one is enough to make me -1.

This is well thought out and looks like a net-positive change. If there are more iterations on the spec, consider making some of the minor changes I've suggested, but I wouldn't worry too much about them.

However, I strongly oppose having two zeromq drivers for a few reasons. The biggest one is that this will be _extremely_ difficult to migrate to from the old driver. I suggest that there be one driver, and that it support _both_ methods of communication for some time. This will allow users to make a rolling release of new oslo.messaging, followed by a rolling configuration change. Making them select a whole new driver and roll it out _all at once_ is a massive burden on the operators, far more of a burden than carrying a few extra PUSH/PULL sockets while this rollout is ongoing. Once a site has rolled everything out, a config option to turn off legacy mode would relieve them of that cost.

I am not a user of zmq, so take my words with that grain of salt. However, I'd like to see the thoughts from operators who have already deployed with zmq, and how they plan to migrate to a whole new driver, before this spec is approved."}, {'account_id': 13290, 'date': '2015-04-14 13:27:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi, Clint!
Thank you very much for your comments. I'll try to answer on some notes right here.

> this will be _extremely_ difficult to migrate to from the old driver.
> I'd like to see the thoughts from operators who have already deployed with zmq, and how they plan to migrate to a whole new driver

I don't think the current upstream implementation of the zmq driver could be used somewhere else than on devstack single-node [2]. I know that Li Ma made some multi-node deployment, but he used his own fixed implementation of zmq driver.

So, I suppose migration shouldn't be a problem at all.

I'm also not going to change current options (maybe add some new ones with default values) and oslo.messaging API, so [1] should be valid after the change. 

> there be one driver, and that it support _both_ methods of communication for some time.

Especially this may cause a lot of pain for us to implement these changes in existing driver. Unfortunately current implementation is badly extendable. I can bring some examples of code which make me to think so. There will be a lot of rewriting(refactoring) work which can be omitted if we leave the current driver as is. Actually I'm not going to keep the legacy driver forever and support both implementations, but we can't just throw it out before we have some stable new implementation.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.messaging/zmq_driver.html
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+bug/1381972"}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-04-14 16:57:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Oleksii thanks for your reply. I agree that if the current one is totally broken then making a migration path is not important at all.

Is it possible you could poll openstack-operators@lists.openstack.org and openstack@lists.openstack.org and see if anybody subscribed to those lists is using the current driver? I know that the current one seems broken, but it has existed a long time, and it's possible some people have beaten it into shape enough to work for their use case. Anyway, I think taking a little time to gather data is worth it to make sure the plan will be beneficial to users without too much disruption."}, {'account_id': 3211, 'date': '2015-04-15 01:32:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

NO Problem'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-04-16 20:39:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

It would appear from the mailing list thread that there are users, albeit forked users, who would be affected by a new driver appearing instead of the old driver being improved. This complicates things quite a bit, but I think a valid path would be:

 * Help said users to contribute their fixes here
 * Re-evaluate whether or not the now-fixed zmq driver could be refactored to use REQ/REP/DEALER.

Given that, I think this should be on hold, at least until it's clarified whether or not the current users of zmq would like to participate here or not. If they're unwilling or unable to contribute their fixes here, then that makes the decision to start over a little easier."}, {'account_id': 13290, 'date': '2015-04-16 23:02:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

So unblocking this for now so we can make forward progress. worst case we have 2 drivers (old and new) with the contribs from the already forked driver going into the old driver."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-01 14:24:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

Current zmq driver implementation is built over PUSH/PULL PUB/SUB socket patterns. These kind of sockets are straight-forward one way directed. So, to organize some backward replies (as CALL method does) we need to support two socket pipelines PUSH/PULL for sending messages and subscribe for reply over PUB/SUB.

commit_message:
Change ZeroMQ driver underlying pattern to REQ/REP

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+spec/zmq-req-rep

Current zmq driver implementation is built over PUSH/PULL PUB/SUB socket patterns.
These kind of sockets are straight-forward one way directed.
So, to organize some backward replies (as CALL method does) we need to support
two socket pipelines PUSH/PULL for sending messages and subscribe for reply over PUB/SUB.

I assume that was made because of those days ZeroMQ restrictions.
Now we have two-directions socket types like REQ/REP (Request-Reply).
There is also ROUTER/DEALER async version of REQ/REP.
I'd like to propose to use this pattern in zmq driver.
This will reduce a second socket pipeline and a lot of surrounding code.

Change-Id: I5692e9db94c123d818b6ed63af70054ab1848336

commit_message:
Allow complex filtering with embedded dicts

Allow filtering of searchable data to be done with multiple levels
of dict data, rather than only simple types (string, int, etc).
Two tests are added for testing a dict within the filtering dict,
and a dict within a dict within the filtering dict (to test the
recursive aspect).

Change-Id: I17562bfe6bf5cb6a0dc48c4a693fe755200eee08

[{'created': '2015-04-08 11:01:59.000000000', 'message': 'Spawn RADVD only in the master HA router

Currently radvd is spawned in all the HA routers irrespective of the
state of the router. This approach has the following issues.

1. While processing the internal router ports (i.e., qr-xxx), ha_router
   removes the LLA of the interface and adds it as a VIP to Keepalived conf.
   Radvd daemon is spawned after this operation in the router namespace
   (if the port is associated with any IPv6 subnets). Radvd notices that
   qr-xxx interface does not have the LLA, so does not transmit any Router
   Advts. In this state, VMs fail to acquire IPv6 addresses because of the
   missing RAs. Radvd does not recover even after keepalived configures the
   LLA of the interface. The only solution is to restart/reload radvd daemon.
   Currently keepalived-state-change monitor does not do any radvd related
   operations when a state transition happens. So we endup in this state
   forever.
2. For all the routers in Backup state, qr-xxx interface does not have LLA
   as it is managed by keepalived and configured only on the Master HA router.
   In such agents syslog is flooded with the messages [1] and this can cause
   loss of other useful info.
   [1] - resetting ipv6-allrouters membership on qr-2e373555-97

This patch implements the following.
1. If the router is already in the Master state, we configure the LLA as a VIP
   in keepalived conf but do not delete the LLA of the internal interface.
2. We spawn radvd only if the router is in the Master State.
3. Keepalived-state-change monitor takes care of enabling/disabling radvd upon
   state transitions.

Closes-Bug: #1440699
Change-Id: I351c71d058170265bbb8b56e1f7a3430bd8828d5

commit_message:
Spawn RADVD only in the master HA router

Currently radvd is spawned in all the HA routers irrespective of the
state of the router. This approach has the following issues.

1. While processing the internal router ports (i.e., qr-xxx), ha_router
   removes the LLA of the interface and adds it as a VIP to Keepalived conf.
   Radvd daemon is spawned after this operation in the router namespace
   (if the port is associated with any IPv6 subnets). Radvd notices that
   qr-xxx interface does not have the LLA, so does not transmit any Router
   Advts. In this state, VMs fail to acquire IPv6 addresses because of the
   missing RAs. Radvd does not recover even after keepalived configures the
   LLA of the interface. The only solution is to restart/reload radvd daemon.
   Currently keepalived-state-change monitor does not do any radvd related
   operations when a state transition happens. So we endup in this state
   forever.
2. For all the routers in Backup state, qr-xxx interface does not have LLA
   as it is managed by keepalived and configured only on the Master HA router.
   In such agents syslog is flooded with the messages [1] and this can cause
   loss of other useful info.
   [1] - resetting ipv6-allrouters membership on qr-2e373555-97

This patch implements the following.
1. If the router is already in the Master state, we configure the LLA as a VIP
   in keepalived conf but do not delete the LLA of the internal interface.
2. We spawn radvd only if the router is in the Master State.
3. Keepalived-state-change monitor takes care of enabling/disabling radvd upon
   state transitions.

Closes-Bug: #1440699
Change-Id: I351c71d058170265bbb8b56e1f7a3430bd8828d5

commit_message:
Update pyScss and django-pyscss

pyScss <1.3 has an ordering bug which results in @imports
being included in semi-random order. This breaks the ordering
of the CSS parts of bootstrap, which breaks some critical
elements of bootstrap.

Change-Id: I77d6f41fe7c9617298484969220f6fdfe82c3c36
Depends-On: Idec7ce039b57476ce20b7b678431459c2ca0bdbf

commit_message:
Added branch creation to yaql ACL

To comply with the new governance for libraries yaql has to define
stable branches.
This patch allows yaql-release team to create new stable branches and
yaql-milestone team to maintain them.

Change-Id: If15ab12ffabe035b676fb46dabe46531689244ab

commit_message:
neutron subnet-create requires args at the end

The network name must be next to the CIDR otherwise `neutron
subnet-create` gets confused.

Change-Id: Ie8b19d3824e5e25f80c61f0794595813c80b98da

commit_message:
devstack: Give example of custom ovs git repo.

Provide an example of how to configure a custom OVS git repo.  This is
useful at the moment as the latest patches to make OVN work are not
all merged, so you may want to test from a branch that has them
applied already.

Change-Id: Ic1cacbee2d05c0889d2cc10f0d96d0fa1f45d60e

commit_message:
devstack: Fix git repo name assumptions.

Some parts of the devstack plugin assumed the git repo would always be
ovs.git.  Make it figure that out from the git repo URL.

Change-Id: I05764b6d55571b33a9ffed5eb687804d16021c50

This adds a non-voting functional test job for python-glanceclient. Once
the tests pass reliably it will be set to voting.

The initial code was gathering all of the FC ports for certain
operations.  This could lead to very long delays as the inactive ports
would run operations, and would eventually time out.

This change will only return the active ports for the VIOSes, resulting
in faster operations when dealing with storage.

Change-Id: I5c10e8e91ef6936f6c6c44644de54db3b18a41d5
'}]
commit_message:
Use the active WWPNs for connections

The initial code was gathering all of the FC ports for certain
operations.  This could lead to very long delays as the inactive ports
would run operations, and would eventually time out.

This change will only return the active ports for the VIOSes, resulting
in faster operations when dealing with storage.

Change-Id: I5c10e8e91ef6936f6c6c44644de54db3b18a41d5

commit_message:
Add notes about official sub-projects.

There was recently a thread on openstack-dev titled "A big tent home
for Neutron backend code."

The thread began here:

    http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-April/062310.html

and has roughly ended up here:

    http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-April/062853.html

This patch is an attempt to reflect the end of that thread with
updates to docs.

Any further discussion should just continue on openstack-dev to avoid
forking the discussion between openstack-dev and gerrit.

Change-Id: I48dbe8ac69e60fbfd5e5082844004aaf9fdce539

In my option this affects all the services not only "compute". Why not have them disabled by default?'}, {'account_id': 14927, 'date': '2015-04-19 16:13:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2015-04-19 23:15:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'd like to explore this idea a bit further please.

I can see a need to not schedule user instances to freshly commissioned hypervisor nodes until those nodes have been verified. However, disabling the service doesn't seem the best way to me -- how are you validating the configuration if the service is disabled?

What if we instead supported bringing all new hypervisor nodes online in a specific host aggregate? That would meant that an admin could then boot and instance via the API and verify that everything works before releasing the hypervisor node for general use.

I could see admins automating this in their deployment even -- commission the hypervisor node, add it to the aggregate, perform automated checks including booting an instance, remove from aggregate when verified.

I'd be interested in if the ops community thinks this is a viable alternative."}, {'account_id': 6687, 'date': '2015-04-20 17:28:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6589, 'date': '2015-04-20 17:39:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

This looks good to me now.

Addressing Michael's comment about operator feedback:

I might be wrong on this, but I believe an admin level account can still schedule a build to a compute service that is disabled. That way admins can validate that the host is operating correctly before enabling the service. I believe that was what the operators in the room at the PHL meetup agreed was the ideal work flow."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-20 18:07:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/37/175037/2/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/251ae97/ : SUCCESS in 1m 44s'}, {'account_id': 7254, 'date': '2015-04-20 18:15:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

if using AZ's any account with access to the "force_host" security context can build to a disabled host.

if not i filed a blueprint for adding similar functionality to the default cells based scheduling hints:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/disabled-host-override-for-builds'}, {'account_id': 7254, 'date': '2015-04-20 18:17:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2015-04-20 19:31:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Thanks for answering my question. Another quick one I just thought of...

How do we stop this being confusing for new operators with small deployments? This totally makes sense for established installs, but I worry that new deployments of only a couple of hypervisors will sit around wondering why scheduling isn't working because they didn't read the docs and enable their hypervisors?

Could we perhaps for example only disable if a minimum number of enabled hypervisors are present in the deploy?"}, {'account_id': 6589, 'date': '2015-04-20 19:58:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

That seems like it would overly complicate the code and the docs and the admins. Small scale things would work automatically but as they grow stuff stopped working automatically when they hit an arbitrary size.

Stepping back a moment, there IS a config item, enable_new_services. I honestly /do/ think its reasonable to have this default to yes, and sites that are concerned about bringing new services online without testing can change this config entry to false in their deployments. So I'm ambivalent on the change. Ops have a toggle we can use, it's just a matter of what that default should be."}, {'account_id': 9500, 'date': '2015-04-20 20:16:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think it's fair to have the default to new nodes coming up enabled. Operators that know they want this will just configure it as such. It will be far less confusing for new users or smaller operations."}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2015-04-21 11:55:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I think that can be done using config mgmt systems and not being in Nova upstream. If so, it would just add one more step for an install that would create more difficulty for newcomers IMHO.'}, {'account_id': 6687, 'date': '2015-04-28 10:46:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I wasn't aware of the enable_new_services configuration flag, either. That will take care of what I need. Belmiro's patch for the disabled_reason handles the other parts of the spec."}, {'account_id': 6687, 'date': '2015-05-01 13:08:13.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

enable_new_services will accomplish the large operators goal, Belmiro's patches will provide disabled reasons when enable_new_services is set to False. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/136645/"}]

commit_message:
Default Service Node Status to Disabled

At the PHL Operators meetup, the large deployments group concluded new compute
capacity should be disabled by default. The group cited production issues
where instance failures were caused by untested compute provisioning. Disabling
new services by default is safer and allows operators to fully test
new before releasing it for use.

blueprint disable-compute-default

Change-Id: I29d5b3cf55985cd007a86cc7c507bd589d1e0f0b

commit_message:
Correct case on RPMs in bindep fallback

Unfortunately yum is case-sensitive, so to avoid implementing
additional search-and-match logic in bindep we should just respect
this platform quirk.

Change-Id: I5d2e95ad908a493966fb4edfe1fd5c5653ac08a7

Bind manila-ui project changes to IRC channel openstack-manila

API interaction, along with what is actually returned, which should

'}]
commit_message:
Change ironic maintenance method to align with power method

Upon obtaining a better understanding of the Ironicclient and Ironic
API interaction, along with what is actually returned, which should
be None, it makes sense to have set_machine_maintenance_state match
set_power_state in behavior.

Change-Id: I2899f290c0521e35d010dc9246b590ca9e949214

commit_message:
Add Ironic machine power state pass-through

Adding machine power state passthrough in the form of
a _set_machine_power_state method, along with wrapper methods
set_machine_power_on, set_machine_power_off and
set_machine_power_reboot.

Tests to utilize the on, off, and reboot methods have been
which all invoke the _set_machine_power_state method.

commit_message:
Change apache service to restart

After fixing the apache service issue with Ubuntu14.04, restart
command should work better that manual stop/start. While stopping
and starting a service using scripts, it can sometimes be too fast
to give time to the service to respond properly and cause error
status and more races.

Change-Id: I84b2271f07a10ce1a29403312736272221895c35

commit_message:
Add minor OperatorCloud documentation

The documentation for the OperatorCloud methods with docstrings will not
be generated unless the class itself has a docstring. This adds a simple
docstring just to get the documentation generated.

Also adds a link to the CONTRIBUTING.rst doc pointing to the project
documentation.

Change-Id: I535289a938f68895c19b5e226d2e2302b566d00d

commit_message:
Allow for int or string ID comparisons

Some IDs are clearly strings (e.g., UUIDs) and some look like integers
(e.g., flavor ID of '100'). Let's make it easy for a user by allowing
for string or int. For example:

    flavor = cloud.get_flavor(100)

or

    flavor = cloud.get_flavor('100')

The former example using the int doesn't work, but this fixes that.

Change-Id: If201352a9917d7c8fba7b386b38fced9949f00a9

commit_message:
Basic infrastructure for HA Guide conversion to RST

The High Availability Guide is being rewritten and the team
has chosen to use RST.  This patch puts the infrastructure in
place.  Existing content will be improved and moved over, and
new content will be added here rather than the docbook.

The tox.ini file excludes this content from being published at
this time.

To generate the HA guide, use:  tox -e ha

Change-Id: If72e0b89ce1b561bce4439b4811256b620856954

subject: Allow master flavor specification for docker swarm
messages:
[{'account_id': 11650, 'date': '2015-04-30 16:18:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-30 16:49:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-magnum-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/47/179147/1/check/gate-magnum-pep8/7b93d10/ : SUCCESS in 1m 48s
- gate-magnum-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/47/179147/1/check/gate-magnum-docs/36161d0//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 53s
- gate-magnum-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/47/179147/1/check/gate-magnum-python27/57ce8bf/ : SUCCESS in 2m 14s
- check-functional-dsvm-magnum http://logs.openstack.org/47/179147/1/check/check-functional-dsvm-magnum/c7a768f/ : SUCCESS in 30m 58s (non-voting)
- gate-magnum-tox-bandit http://logs.openstack.org/47/179147/1/check/gate-magnum-tox-bandit/51ef685/ : SUCCESS in 1m 44s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2015-04-30 16:55:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'm not sure this is really a good idea, or even tech debt.

For our Kubernetes bay, the master is a special non-node instance that is running multiple control services and isn't running the minion services. Thus, it can't have containers allocated to it. So ,it makes sense to specify a different flavor from the test of the cluster.

When it comes to our Swarm bay, the master is simply a normal node instance, that just happens to be running the swarm manager service along side the swarm agent service. It functions just like any other node in the cluster and can have containers allocated to it. Thus, I think it's just going to be confusing having two different flavor parameters for the swarm bay."}, {'account_id': 11650, 'date': '2015-05-01 09:29:56.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Abandoned due to Andrew's comments. Having master flavor is likely to confuse users when creating swarm bay models."}]

commit_message:
Correct LICENSE tag.

Set LICENSE to MIT as per https://github.com/angular/angular.js/blob/master/LICENSE.

The license name is in the SPDX format (https://spdx.org/licenses/),
OSI approved, and thus Open https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Open

Bump build #.

Change-Id: I74558c0cd6a771bb83fefabbc14cd182d4fa0b45

commit_message:
Remove region_name from service catalog

This would allow you to save a region_name on the catalog so that all
your responses were relative to that region_name. This was deprecated,
if you want to search by region name you have to provide it.

Change-Id: Idd7a62a6ce44c3697f62939038d0322482f1e527

This was used to affect the urls that were returned from the catalog.
This should never have been here and is deprecated.

commit_message:
Adds config files to Install and configure storage nodes

Configuration files for container-reconciler and object-expirer
 are not provided during the swift install. This commit adds
 them to the install and configure storage node components section.

Change-Id: Iccc33509f0917652c686e9e0f1baa23cbde2f7bc
Closes-Bug: #1437185

commit_message:
Add checking for name during plugin creation

Currently plugin builder can verify correctness only
after plugin was created. It gives to user possibility
creates plugin with incorrect name. This fix provides
validation for name on creation stage.

Change-Id: Ib54313fac6b246288838e48ce483046e47a5a7bb
Closes-Bug: #1439760

commit_message:
Use the AccessInfoPlugin from keystoneclient

The AccessInfoPlugin that is mentioned in the comments is now available
from keystoneclient. We should use that instead of our own copy.

Change-Id: I52f0f7eceae541dd931ff8554149d2bd90200a5e

commit_message:
Dell SC driver calls out the wrong REST API version

On initialization of the session with the Dell REST
API the dell api version was incorrectly specified.
It should be 2.0 rather than 1.5.

Change-Id: I47ef63c24305b23125802012aa3c9dfde76813fd
Closes-Bug: #1446868

commit_message:
Context: is_admin==True implies is_advsvc=True

With this change is the is_admin parameter is set to True when
creating a context, the is_advsvc property is set to True as well,
without executing a pointless check with policy engine.

Closes-Bug: #1450244

Change-Id: I0a21a82692665599260d07c00c55df18fc926eb5

commit_message:
Add min_size and max_size properties to Cluster

This patch added min_size and max_size properties to Cluster. Now
before cluster creating and updating, size related validation will
be done by comparing min_size/max_size/desired_capacity.

TODO:
  - Do size validation before node adding/deleting/migrating
  - Do size validation before cluster scaling
  - Heat stack update need support from SDK

Change-Id: Ibf792f5152f7bd5ada53ec7755bbe92616dbdcd5
Implements: blueprint add-size-limitation-properties-to-cluster

commit_message:
A sample spec complex scaling policy

We are supporting complex scaling policies that allow users to specify
conditions for each policy. I'm not sure if we should make this a
generic case for all.

Change-Id: Iac851844a1fe23a654241031b93d05552bbfce13

commit_message:
Adding "requires" to "task-defaults" clause

* Reverse workflows can now use "requires" declared in
  "task-defaults", for example, to have all tasks
  depending on a configured task (except this task itself)
* Fixed a bug with "processed" flag, it shouldn't be taken
  into account for reverse workflows because if say task3
  depends on task2 then these tasks can't depend on a task1
  at the same time

Change-Id: Iad113e405f43125b37d16b91fcf448c21cd354e6
(cherry picked from commit fa0102354b6fd5f865fc33eb2f703f658bfe98b1)

commit_message:
Adding "requires" to "task-defaults" clause

* Reverse workflows can now use "requires" declared in
  "task-defaults", for example, to have all tasks
  depending on a configured task (except this task itself)
* Fixed a bug with "processed" flag, it shouldn't be taken
  into account for reverse workflows because if say task3
  depends on task2 then these tasks can't depend on a task1
  at the same time

Currently when doing an evacuate the neutron host_id binding for
the port isn't updated.

Currently in rebuild_instance() we call
self.network_api.setup_networks_on_host() but this doesn't actually
do anything for neutron.

problems elsewhere.

commit_message:
Fix binding:host_id for neutron on evacuate

Currently when doing an evacuate the neutron host_id binding for
the port isn't updated.

Currently in rebuild_instance() we call
self.network_api.setup_networks_on_host() but this doesn't actually
do anything for neutron.

For neutron the cleanest fix would be to change rebuild_instance()
to call self.network_api.setup_instance_network_on_host() but this
might break nova-network.

So as a test we're going to modify neutron's
setup_networks_on_host() to act the same as
setup_instance_network_on_host().  Hopefully this won't cause
problems elsewhere.

Change-Id: I5e420075400afbe064231be38f06438f48dd1178
Closes-Bug: #1444171

commit_message:
Update trove config database connection

In Kilo, the sql_connection parameter was deprecated for trove.
This patch moves the sql connection to the [database] section.

Change-Id: Ic6391a14cf4cc4e8015ce3132502105b04874eba
Closes-Bug: 1434943

commit_message:
Compatibility fix for pyscss 1.3.4

This commit alters the action-list.scss file so it is compatible
with the newer version of pyScss (1.3.4+), allowing us to
upgrade to that version.

This change is a prerequisite for the update to get into the
global requirements so that that change can pass testing.

Change-Id: Idec7ce039b57476ce20b7b678431459c2ca0bdbf
Co-Authored-By: Kelly Domico <kelly.domico@hp.com>

The auth_token middleware moved from keystoneclient.middleware to
keystonemiddleware.

commit_message:
Rename _discover module

_discover was private in keystoneclient because there was a circular
dependency. All the functions within have always been public as they
were imported into the keystoneclient.discover file.

Rename now we don't have to worry about our imports.

Change-Id: I4b6afcefd1376f8d2d0a8d2f602f967a1febf3f1

This was unfortunate.  I reviewed what happened in detail because I didn't understand at first.  Here is my summary.

[1] was merged first to master.  [2] merged a few days later on to master and had been rebased to include the changes introduced by [1].

[1] was cherry-picked as [3] and is pretty much identical to what was proposed to master.  [2] was cherry-picked as [4] but had to work around the fact that [3] hadn't merged yet.  So, [4] had a lesser scope than [2].  Given the context at the time, it seemed like the right thing to do.

Both [3] and [4] merged to juno around the same time and without conflict.  Ideally, we would have seen that the two were both proposed, identified the dependency between them, and properly serialized them on to Juno.  But, things happen and we didn't connect the dots.  Also, this is the nature of cherry-picking, you often don't have the same context and you have to react.  So, [3] added log statements that [2] had removed but [4] didn't remove them on stable/juno.

The bottom line is that this proposed patch merely picks up part of the original fix in [2] that was missing from [4] because of the lacking context of [3].  I think it is the right thing to do.

Another way to look at it:  we get the same end result if we revert [4] and then cherry-pick [2] again to Juno.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/147455
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/149784
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/153181
[4] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/164329"}, {'account_id': 5209, 'date': '2015-04-16 22:35:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-04-16 22:38:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Food for thought.  Could [2] have had a UT written to test for the original problem (log messages in the loop) and caught the problem at gate time?  I think it would've been spit out of the gate because it would've been tested in context with [3] merged in already.  Should we add that test to this patch?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-16 22:44:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Remove Debug Traces from _output_hosts_file

On the stable/juno branch, bug #1414218 should have been fixed
by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/164329 (merged April 1st).
This patch removed LOG.debug statement from for-loop of method
_output_hosts_file(). However patch
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/153181 (also merged April 1st)
added LOG.debug statements to the for-loop of the same method.
The result is bug 1414218 isn't fixed on the stable/juno branch.
In order to have bug 1414218 fixed on the stable/juno branch the
LOG.debug statements in the for-loop of _output_hosts_file is
removed.

Change-Id: I7e620443d9835b65d276c1aed055cffc3bf4f13b
related-bug: #1414218
closes-bug: #1445202

commit_message:
Prevent false positives of UPDATE_COMPLETE in integration tests

Use the updated_at field in the stack output to check for
false positives of UPDATE_COMPLETE.

Partially-Closes Bug: #1433340

Change-Id: I8e68a2764741cc19305a0db7825322807b6508f3

commit_message:
Add timeout hidden parameter to AWS LB

Current implemenatation contains WaitCondition resource with timeout
equal 600. It is enough for fast hardware, unortunatelly thre are some
situation when need more time for downloading and installation all
related packages. As good example can be used our Heat gate job,
where provisioning one vm take more then 10 minutes.
This patch add paramater for WaitCondition timeout. Now it can be used
to change wait time for provisioning instance with all necessary packages.

Change-Id: Id80b2655f7e218cf884b86838d28588b865a5e56

commit_message:
Enable SecurityGroups property for AWS LB resource

AWS LB has SecurityGroups property, but it's not implemented.
This patch adds turn on this option by using SecurityGroups in nested
template as parameter and property for AWS::EC2::Instance.

Change-Id: I922cc97291179c79d1451a38cbb9e16933d703ef
Closes-Bug: #1443947

The instructions for how to build instances with ISO images is
incorrect in config-reference/iso-support. Following the original
instruction, users are unable to create functional VMs, they will
stuck at system installation and rebooting.

This patch addes instructions about how to use ISO images to create
functional VMs without any third party softwares (just OpenStack).

commit_message:
Support for ISO images in OpenStack Configuration Reference is incorrect

The instructions for how to build instances with ISO images is
incorrect in config-reference/iso-support. Following the original
instruction, users are unable to create functional instances, they
will stuck at system installation and rebooting.

This patch addes instructions about how to use ISO images to create
functional VMs without any third party softwares (just OpenStack).

Change-Id: I6c03cb8f7a6e5ca5a30a4f78b26965c47b7c397a
Closes-Bug:#1448894

Deprecate auth_token authentication

Applications should be using the standard authentication plugins
rather than auth_token authentication.

commit_message:
Update the TOSCA monitoring use case

Update the template with remaining components including elasticsearch,
logstash, kibana, rsyslog, collectd and nodejs samplea application. These
templates has been discussed and reviewed by TOSCA TC.

Change-Id: Ie842c288cbb2bd2d81e50c85b8b417ad7c5716dc

client is scoped to. Change this to creating a new project as this will fail if
the admin client is scoped to a domain instead of a project.

Also specify domain information when creating users and projects. If not
specified the default domain for create_user and create_project is 'default',
however if not specified at authentication time the default user domain is
CONF.identity.admin_domain_name - which may not be default.

commit_message:
Create a new project for trusts tests

The trusts tests were originally being done in the project that the admin
client is scoped to. Change this to creating a new project as this will fail if
the admin client is scoped to a domain instead of a project.

Also specify domain information when creating users and projects. If not
specified the default domain for create_user and create_project is 'default',
however if not specified at authentication time the default user domain is
CONF.identity.admin_domain_name - which may not be default.

Change-Id: I4ab3383f48894d00c1b59abdb97ab483e6ca5270

commit_message:
Don't use iterator in search for tunnel type

Changing dictionary size while using iterator causes RuntimeError. This
can happen in local vlan mapping under certain program flows. This patch
changes iteritems() to values() that returns list and thus preventing
from failure if local vlan mapping changes during creating tunnels.

Change-Id: I8a858d5c53e85f83a582f34205f9afa214cb4d58
Closes-Bug: 1449944

commit_message:
Add description & example for isServer property in Magic Search

Added description and example of setting isServer property to indicate
facet is server side and should be rendered as such.

Change-Id: Icbea0ce55b5a51dab9986b0e6488fbf8822f7196
Closes-bug: #1449651

commit_message:
Establish baseline JSCS configuration

Establishes the ability to have JSCS (JS Code Style) run from the
run_tests.sh script.  Also provides basis for code style configuration.

Co-Authored-By: Brian Tully <brian.tully@hp.com>
Change-Id: Ib22da5ae05c353d12507a1809ec79e93379acecf
Closes-Bug: 1450626

commit_message:
Move logging sample to use oslo_log

etc/cinder/logging_sample.conf needs an update to refer to
oslo_log, not cinder.openstack.common.log for its ContextFormatter.

Change-Id: I8bc2618124dfffc54d15fc5615bb1884d74988f4
Closes-Bug: #1450500

commit_message:
Cleanup fixed_name logic in test_list_server_filters

This commit cleans up the logic for determining the fixed network name
to use for test list server filters. Previously it had an unnecessary
if block to handle the case where getting a network name failed. This
simplifies the logic to just use a get() on the dictionary which will
default to false.

Change-Id: I356124459610342c8f7906397e23d58cbfad99bb

Added more unit-tests to guestagent

More tests have been added to improve code-coverage
of following code-files:

- trove/guestagent/api.py
- trove/guestagent/pkg.py
- trove/guestagent/volume.py
- trove/guestagent/common/operating_system.py
- trove/guestagent/datastore/mysql/manager.py
- trove/guestagent/datastore/mysql/service.py

This patchset also resolves some bugs.

Change-Id: I38e5d2e0e9b2213997e8cea9fbee856c62daa377
Closes-Bug: #1449480
Closes-Bug: #1449485

commit_message:
Update pod manifest parsing according to v1beta3

Now that Kubernetes 0.15.0 release is supported and it has
v1beta3, the manifest structure has changed from v1beta1 to
v1beta3. This change implements the v1beta3 manifest parsing
logic.

Change-Id: Iaebe9fa29ba81d4f49a1b9fb1a547757b96520da
Partially-Implements: blueprint python-k8sclient

commit_message:
Update Kubernetes version for supporting v1beta3.

Kubernetes v1beta3 API is enabled in release 0.15.0.
So this change updated the release version in doc.

Change-Id: I2754c5453f511f4a4ceb9da9644929a340f346c3
Partially-Implements: blueprint python-k8sclient

commit_message:
fixed_network should be fixed_network_cidr

fixed_network should be fixed_network_cidr as this is the value that
exists in the heat template.

Update tests to use a cidr address string rather than a text string to
match the parameters expected contents.

Change-Id: I624b95930f9eb506abfb2e29beea8d83878ea142
Closes-Bug: 1450140

[{'created': '2015-04-28 01:06:48.000000000', 'message': 'Remove the is_id boolean check for domains

The _stack_domain_is_id is a boolean that tells you if the value in
self.stack_domain is a name or id value.

This is clunky. Replace it with just saving the id or name into their

Change-Id: I9f6ec6b414174870317aa167e3c953c6844ccab9
'}]
commit_message:
Remove the is_id boolean check for domains

The _stack_domain_is_id is a boolean that tells you if the value in
self.stack_domain is a name or id value.

This is clunky. Replace it with just saving the id or name into their
own variables as None values in auth plugins are ignored.

commit_message:
Allow instances to attach to shared external nets

Allow non-admin tenants to attach instances to external networks
from Neutron if the networks are also marked as shared.

Conflicts:
	nova/network/neutronv2/api.py
	nova/tests/network/test_neutronv2.py

Closes-Bug: #1413837
Change-Id: I4de08f4c296f5c05b49294599d6b2b8a41205213
(cherry picked from commit a98aa603550ad4d9f8d16de8c7acd0819680a028)

commit_message:
Refactored barbican.py for better testability

We heavily refactored barbican.py and its respective
tests in order to ensure better testing practices.
The tests no longer rely on executing through cliff.
Cliff was responsible for suppressing errors.

Change-Id: I820c90a0d197d6470b36b5767b9f983572a7ff0f

have support for it.

commit_message:
Install packages from plugin.sh

The plugin installs redis packages when needed but it doesn't do the
same for mongodb. This patch makes sure the required mongodb packages
are installed.

Change-Id: Ifef3d043cc05323a964ac3f3eac2f3505b267b82
Depends-On: 9643dcbf073d187d1ec32253c039ede6ba8b4d59

commit_message:
Correct the tag merge script logic

The previous iteration did not take into account that the most
recent tag on master is likely to have been a release candidate, and
therefore have the same major+minor value as the incoming release.
Also tags pushed to non-stable branches should be skipped.

Change-Id: I339df1d88ddaedb193b1b246a2c21a433c11495c

and capitalization section in the wiki

[{'account_id': 15663, 'date': '2015-04-30 02:31:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-04-30 02:32:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

commit_message:
Add apps needed for a CI/CD pipeline.

Attis-- wrapper app that deploys and configures the CI/CD infrastructure
OpenLDAP-- openLDAP app; Create user jenkins/openstack for authentication
Gerrit-- Gerrit app that uses OpenLDAP for authentication; create user gerrit
Jenkins-- Jenkins app that uses OpenLDAP for authentication

Change-Id: I583e574717d86aa081d1c1755d14acd831ec04ca

commit_message:
Adjust the way we find the set of tags to check for "latest"

Only look at tags on the current branch when trying to determine the
latest release.

Change-Id: If33efee5499bcc4df7d4dfe86a953bde579903e0

commit_message:
Ignore non-numerical releases in highest_semver.py

Now that we are no longer using alpha releases, we don't need to process
non-numerical version numbers. Ignore anything that we can't convert to
a sequence of integers.

Change-Id: Idf18bcd841f9fd435641211b773574c2d85a1694

and capitalization section in the wiki

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Conventions

commit_message:
Download of translations not properly disabled in APT

The wrong APT config name is used to disable download of translations.
It's Acquire::Languages, not APT::Acquire::Languages.

Change-Id: Ie0c12d444bab19b4486845944ef51031e9133470
Closes-bug: #1436523

(5 comments)

I think this is missing some validation checks.  The job should be validated concerning mains/libs, and I think the job_execution configs should be validated on submission and required to include a topology name.

Also, it occurs to me that if Storm is using the Spark implementation as a base, with wrappers around shell commands and the launch_command.py script as the job launcher, there may be very little difference between Spark EDP and Storm EDP.

I think it may well be worth the time to look at the differences and then potentially refactor the Spark EDP engine so that we can have a common base engine for job types that are implemented in this way. 

It looks to me (after a quick read) like the essential differences here are the shell commands that are submitted to implement run_job, cancel_job, and get_status but the handling of the job itself is all the same (pid files, launch_command.py, the job dirs, etc).

What if we created something like a "ShellCommandEDPEngine"
and then derived SparkEDPEngine and StormEDPEngine (and others in the future) from the common base?'}, {'account_id': 8932, 'date': '2015-03-31 13:28:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(5 comments)'}, {'account_id': 8932, 'date': '2015-03-31 14:05:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Trevor, regarding the usage of PID and dir_files, I kept so it would break to return of the launch_command.py but the pid doesn't really work for storm, i tried manually and I cant control job flow with the pid just the topology name. Maybe we can implement a base and derive but they will have some differences that will be hard to manage"}, {'account_id': 8932, 'date': '2015-03-31 14:43:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8932, 'date': '2015-03-31 14:44:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 8932, 'date': '2015-03-31 15:49:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Storm EDP implementation

Implementation of Storm EDP. This will allow users to submit Storm Jobs
via UI.
This patch implements the EDP engine, Storm Job Type.

Implements: bp storm-edp

Change-Id: I7d5937f26df715ef66826396a6387ab512af1f47

commit_message:
Add apps needed for a CI/CD pipeline.

Attis-- wrapper app that deploys and configures the CI/CD infrastructure
OpenLDAP-- openLDAP app; Create user jenkins/openstack for authentication
Gerrit-- Gerrit app that uses OpenLDAP for authentication; create user gerrit
Jenkins-- Jenkins app that uses OpenLDAP for authentication

Change-Id: I6eafbf845f5161d54d9a12e755fcab00c1916e11

Move the files to packages subdirectory

Change-Id: I171280806bdf3bc83bbf710280f6f0f788b35773

commit_message:
Add apps needed for a CI/CD pipeline.

Attis-- wrapper app that deploys and configures the CI/CD infrastructure
OpenLDAP-- openLDAP app; Create user jenkins/openstack for authentication
Gerrit-- Gerrit app that uses OpenLDAP for authentication; create user gerrit
Jenkins-- Jenkins app that uses OpenLDAP for authentication

Change-Id: I171280806bdf3bc83bbf710280f6f0f788b35773

Move files to subdirectory package

Change-Id: I583e574717d86aa081d1c1755d14acd831ec04ca

commit_message:
Bumped the heat client to the latest release

This resolves an issue with the heat client not respecting the
internalURL when it should be.

Change-Id: I863ff2e2ef6db1d4d76e4000ed0d00214ca65488
(cherry picked from commit 6be8b306572505d17045dbbe9c53ebc0ab51fd9a)

commit_message:
Dont install db packages on compute nodes

The db access packages should not be installed on compute worker
nodes.
Requires a patch to Common for wrappers and role.

Change-Id: I1909b3b5b3772e9586524a3355e03d62974f9104
Partial-Bug: #1448255

commit_message:
Corrects order of parameters to assertEqual

The correct order of parameters to assertEqual is (expected,
actual).
It makes the assertion message more meaningful when there is
a failure.

Change-Id: I1ad41bcbec30442785f4cdabb234980e336312d5
Closes-Bug: #1277104
Partial-Bug: #1445131

commit_message:
Default glance swift_backend to use local swift

The default values should use the local swift installation, since these
are only used when the glance backend is set to "swift" it won't matter
if there is no local swift when the backend is set to "file".

Adjust AIO script to use the defaults.

Move the configuration values from user_secrets.yml into
user_variables.yml since these are not passwords that should be set.
Additionally comment them out by default.

commit_message:
Corrects order of parameters to assertEqual

The correct order of parameters to assertEqual is (expected,
actual).
It makes the assertion message more meaningful when there is
a failure.

Change-Id: Ifd35dbf6a6157c6ec7607e8ace6757b12f47657d
Closes-Bug: #1277104

commit_message:
Merge tags from stable branches to master

We no longer use proposed branches, so should merge tags from stable
branches to master but only when appropriate.

commit_message:
Eliminate extra queries used to retrieve gw_ports

The _get_sync_routers method was calling get_routers and
then getting the gateway ports from the db in a separate
get_ports call. This extra call is unnecessary since is
already an SQL relationship directly between the router
and it's gw_port.

This patch eliminates all of the additional gw_port retrieval
logic by replacing the get_routers call with a _get_collection
call to make use of the gw_port object already present on
each router object.

Change-Id: I478bfef8b0273b343aa72bcd6787a486eba4f006
Partial-Bug: #1445412

commit_message:
Deploy base os role firstly in case of multiroles

Reason: complex role like controller can perform complicated actions
which can conflict with base tasks.

commit_message:
Update CORS tests to use config fixture's load_raw_values

The newer version of oslo_config contains a method that allows
us to load raw values into our fixture directly. This patch updates
the relevant unit tests to use this method instead of the manual
load/clear it was doing previously.

Change-Id: I415bed500995c389c4a4bcf9787609a806562018

commit_message:
Revert "Temporarily copy proposed/* ACLs to stable/kilo"

Remove the stable/kilo temporarily release management ACL sections
but don't restore the old proposed/* sections since they're no
longer needed either. At least in spirit....

This reverts commit 639ec1d17e77be63204ddce1851d179de27cd424.
This reverts commit fb04574fc07c13f933aba9e9addc731ec9d6bb2a.
This reverts commit 774f236cf4386435e90f02fb28669c37ed97c2bf.

Change-Id: Ifb5e8ec6175ad0623db9e3c02883255c98149dab

[{'created': '2015-02-10 18:39:29.000000000', 'message': "Add VLAN to network meta if applicable

Certain compute drivers need to determine the VLAN for a VIF at plug
time.  This need can be seen by the existing VMware driver and the
StackForge nova-powervm driver.

This change set provides the VLAN to be included (if applicable) on the
VIF's network object (meta section).  It is not included if the
network's type is not VLAN.  This change supports both nova network
and neutron networks.

By putting this metadata in the VIF's network object, it avoids the
issue where certain drivers are:
 - Detecting which network is being used
 - Invoking specific operations against that network client to gather
   the needed data

This change does not update the drivers themselves, but rather lays the
foundation so that these drivers can take advantage of it.  Subsequent
change sets are required for platform driver utilization.

Change-Id: I6187428caa04d8a7fd878c7d7ff11fd84c656cab

commit_message:
Add VLAN to network meta if applicable

Certain compute drivers need to determine the VLAN for a VIF at plug
time.  This need can be seen by the existing VMware driver and others
that separate out VIF logic based on Neutron or Nova network.  This
goes against the purpose of the nova network API abstraction, which is
meant to hide if the admin is using Neutron or Nova backed networks.

This change set provides the VLAN to be included (if applicable) on the
VIF's network object (meta section).  It is not included if the
network's type is not VLAN.  This change supports both nova network
and neutron networks.

By putting this metadata in the VIF's network object, it avoids the
issue where certain drivers are:
 - Detecting which network is being used
 - Invoking specific operations against that network client to gather
   the needed data

This change does not update the drivers themselves, but rather lays the
foundation so that these drivers can take advantage of it.  Subsequent
change sets are required for platform driver utilization.

Change-Id: I6187428caa04d8a7fd878c7d7ff11fd84c656cab

commit_message:
Optimize the VIOS specification in driver

This change optimizes the use of the VIOSes in the driver.  It does so
by:
 - Removing an excess call to capture the VIOSes in the driver start up.
 - Querying only for the active VIOSes within the vscsi volume driver.

This not only makes the code run quicker, it is also more correct
functionally.  It no longer tries to connect to VIOSes that may be down
for maintenance purposes.

Change-Id: I718752385837c021c8d0f429ab71f4f7e27c0dd6

[{'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2015-03-04 00:38:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-03-04 00:38:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-03-04 02:24:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

just looking this over, no score, but I am surprised...

This checks if the file on disk, chopped up according to the segment size given as the command line argument would result in the made up checksum of the uploaded manifest

... which seems backwards ...

What I think our client *really* want to know is the file represented by the manifest for this object is the same file as I have on disk (if so, don't re-upload regardless of whatever segment size was used in the original upload or however swift is making up etags on manifests this week etc) - so it seems like a multipart-manfiest=get would be in order...

BTW, those test fixups look AWESOME, that nose thing has driven me crazy for ages - i can't wait to hear the story of how you tracked it down."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-04 02:33:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

(1 comment)

Very nice.

I agree with Clay about losing the capture stream output.

There is a minor regression (or not depending on opinion!) - currently a non-segmented upload with --skip-identical will replace an existing identical xLO because the etags do not match, but a segmented upload will not replace an identical non-xLO (because the etags do match).

With this neither cases will replace - with --skip-identical you cannot change a manifest to be a regular object or vice-versa if contents are identical.

I am inclined to think that --skip-identical should be ignored if the intent is to replace a manifest with a regular object or vice-versa. But given that this review has been around a while and at least makes behavior consistent, I'm happy to +2A.

The dependent patch [1] addresses that - I think it makes sense to keep that separate so the desired behavior can be debated.

patch [1] also adds the new option to sample.conf

commit_message:
Compare each chunk of large objects when uploading

Previously, we compared the ETag from Swift against the MD5 of the
entire large object. However, the ETag for large objects is generally
the MD5 of the concatenation of the ETags for each segment, unless the
object is a DLO whose segments span more than one page of a container
listing. Rather than worry about ETags, just compare each chunk of the
segmented file. This allows the use of --skip-identical when uploading
SLOs and DLOs.

Additionally, there are several test-related improvements:
 * The default arguments for OutputManager are now evaluated on
   construction, rather than on definition, so that
   TestOutputManager.test_instantiation will succeed when using nosetest
   as a test runner. (See also: bug 1251507)
 * An account_username option is now available in the functional tests
   config file for auth systems that do not follow the account:username
   format.
 * CaptureOutput no longer writes to the captured stream, and
   MockHttpTest now captures output. These were polluting test output
   unnecessarily. (See also: bug 1201376)

Change-Id: Ic484e9a0c186c9283c4012c6a2fa77b96b8edf8a
Closes-Bug: #1201376
Closes-Bug: #1379252
Related-Bug: #1251507

[{'created': '2015-04-30 10:32:43.000000000', 'message': "Attaching a multiattach volume to same instance twice should reset state back to 'in-use' and not leave it in 'Attaching'.

When attach is called twice for the same volume and instance the attach_volume checks if the attachment already exists and returns. This leaves the volume in 'Attaching' state. The volume status should be set to 'in-use' if we see the volume is already attached to the given instance.

Change-Id: I2a2d28de59af234300082ab4655b0bc10699d54c
Closes-Bug: #1449980

commit_message:
Revert state if attachment already exists

When attach is called twice for the same volume and instance the
attach_volume checks if the attachment already exists and returns.
This leaves the volume in 'Attaching' state. The volume status should
be reset to 'in-use' if we see the attachment already exists.

Change-Id: I2a2d28de59af234300082ab4655b0bc10699d54c
Closes-Bug: #1449980

commit_message:
Zone ownership tests

* There are three tenants: default, alt, and admin
* Updated config to grab creds for each tenant type
* Reworked clients to make tenant selection simple within test cases
* Added zone ownership test cases
* A bit of other refactoring to put code in more sensible places

Change-Id: I5330b2b1f81ac896300f199b341775594ab14073

commit_message:
Updated release versions for Kilo

The sha's for a few of the services had some last minute changes that
were merged into kilo before the tag as such all of the release entries
have been updated for today's release.

The update-revision.sh script was forward ported from juno into kilo
to ensure that there are no "user errors" when updating kilo in future
revisions.

Implements blueprint: master-kilofication

Change-Id: I3716f3d268475959527237cad98b06dafc1125be

commit_message:
Change keystoneclient to keystoneauth in docs

This was simply the result of:

find -type f | xargs sed -i 's/keystoneclient/keystoneauth/g'
find -type f | xargs sed -i 's/python-keystoneauth/keystoneauth/g'

in the docs directory to fix the build failure.

Will look at a doc rewrite soon.

Change-Id: I05d4be12f31ea47e917dc79e50d17b174bf89938

[{'account_id': 15309, 'date': '2015-04-30 10:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-04-30 10:03:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
Fix translation building and publishing

The translated RST guides were not moved to the publish directories,
move them over for publishing.

Also fix draft publishing for guides that use /draft like install-guide
and config-reference.

Change-Id: Ia80ffc2ab1825d4c1a6b16eef0df39ae28e0c77c

commit_message:
Improvements to README.rst of elements

Improve the formatting of README.rst of elements:
- proper syntax for bash snippets
- improve list formatting
- use list definitions for environment variariables
- remove the explicit bash usage from diskimage-create.sh invocations
- wrap lines at 80 characters
- various small text formattings

Change-Id: I93b4c35b31dac66af22663b2cec426a08fa73bd8

commit_message:
Ensure mocks for lla allocator _write in test_agent

The test test_create_dvr_fip_interfaces_for_restart_l3agent_case was
causing a file fip-linklocal-networks to be created when the tests are
run, this patch ensures that the correct part of the LinkLocalAllocator
is patched to prevent this in the test case.

Change-Id: Ifd0cae56324364b281a9279047b26a182b77905a
Closes-Bug: 1450090

commit_message:
Sahara Data Processing EDP Job Add HBase common lib checkbox

HBase applications written in Java require JARs on the HBase classpath.
Java actions launched from Oozie may reference JARs stored in hdfs
using the `oozie.libpath` configuration value, but there is no
standard HBase directory location in hdfs that is installed with Oozie.
By adding checkbox in the create cluster and job execution page, sahara
provided an option to build the directory at cluster launch time, and also

It definitely fixes the bug. I wish I hadn't lost the VM with my attempt at a fix on it. 

My one thought was that if an external entity was calling the update instead of the recursive call, it could still potentially block the system. The way I was trying to do it was save a variable pending_queries to the table itself (a count of the outstanding ajax calls and decrement as each returned) and check that each time update was called rather than using a count the ajax-update tag. That way, no matter what calls update or how many times, it would never create any new ajax calls until the previous ones were done."}, {'account_id': 8040, 'date': '2014-08-22 14:58:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Dave,

on the hand, your approach may be more bulletproof than mine, while on the other hand I would refrain from doing such thing as storing state in DOM objects (instead of function closures), because that way they could be changed outside of update() function. Perhaps it is a matter of taste.

The thing that bothers me more in this commit is how I implemented testing stub - currently it has the following problem: once $.ajax is restored to the original value, some remaining requests from queue will cause 404 errors - while it doesn't fail the test, it still looks clumsy. I haven't yet found a cleaner way to remove this stub."}, {'account_id': 8040, 'date': '2014-10-06 16:21:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-06 17:35:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fix exponentially growing AJAX updates for table rows

Schedule next table rows update only when the last row was
updated. Since unit-test for this fix relies on a blueprint
replace-qunit-tests-with-jasmine it is moved to a separate commit to
speed up this fix merge, see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179013/

Change-Id: Id603a4fde5713d8f2b85b1dcf72c82c93a87c755
Closes-Bug: #1263665

commit_message:
Add openstack_project_domain to assertion

Currently, a keystone IdP does not provide the domain of the project
when generating SAML assertions. Since it is possible to have two
projects with the same name but in different domains, this patch
adds an additional attribute called "openstack_project_domain"
in the assertion to identify the domain of the project.

Closes-Bug: 1442343
bp assertion-extra-attributes

Change-Id: I62ed73d87f268c73294738845421deb87088326b

commit_message:
Fix _device_to_port_id for non-tap devices

This adjusts the _device_to_port_id function in ML2
to recognize other interfaces that belong to Neutron
under different name prefixes.

Adds unit tests to achieve full converage of _device_to_port_id
method.

Closes-Bug: #1443710
Change-Id: I80284ee67e5876cf5689e49e1592ca1351ae5fa1

commit_message:
devstack: Change tunnel encap to geneve.

The current OVN code only allows geneve or stt for tunnels between
hypervisors.  vxlan is allowed only with gateways (which aren't
supported yet).

Change-Id: Ia5f9d7c562dc3a80637e7b47aadf455f2e2f85b1

commit_message:
local.conf.sample: Enable the rest of OpenStack

Most OpenStack services were disabled in this sample local.conf.
There is enough OVN code available now to do end to end testing, so go
ahead and re-enable everything.

Change-Id: Ie26a6a17042f7a94763aa9ea6ff5da7102d732f9

commit_message:
trim compute smoke tag

Delete the following from the compute smoke tag, these are more
advanced things that should just be caught by full Tempest testing.

 - resize operations

 - all actions except hard reboot

 - all use of proxy APIs (image / volume)

Trim the rest of the tests if it looks like they are doing very
related activities, which means we'll typically only have one or two
smoke tests per class.

Change-Id: Ib91db7204848e8c0892f43251e8937dec6b23232

commit_message:
Add a venv that can generate/write/update the states diagram

Instead of requiring manual understanding of how to generate
the states diagram, add an explicit virtualenv that can be
used to create and generate that docs diagram (and replace the
existing file with it).

Change-Id: I1738da9bf08bfda9b9be01489e8456569a31709e

commit_message:
Add tripleo-core to puppet-tripleo

Adds tripleo-core group to have rights on puppet-tripleo project. The
rights of puppet-manager-core group are kept. This project contains
Puppet code, but is solely used from the TripleO installer, so sometimes
it's not easy to find puppet-manager-core folks to do reviews for this
project to allow dependent changes in TripleO to land. We'd like to
share the permissions on this repository between the two core groups to
expand the number of interested core reviewers and allow an easier
progress on the TripleO Puppet work. The gerritbot is already set up to
notify both IRC channels.

Change-Id: I1f91f851b5800fdf69697fdd88fbd9e41349f6d1

Add in support for a tox pypy target

Since our gate has a gate-python-ironicclient-pypy job,
we should support it in our local test environments.

Change-Id: I825a1206e2c653981ceb2cd2ffe65033bc78a6c4

'}, {'created': '2015-01-19 11:02:20.000000000', 'message': 'Add SLA to check for outliers

The new "max_outliers" SLA checks for the maximum number of outliers based on
the interquartile range of the durations.

Example:
  4.0 4.5 4.0 5.0 12.8 4.3 4.4 10.1 3.0 6.3

  - has 2 outliers (12.8 and 10.1), so:
    {"max_outliers": 2} -> PASS
    {"max_outliers": 1} -> FAIL

'}, {'created': '2015-03-13 06:44:08.000000000', 'message': 'Add SLA to check for outliers

The new "max_outliers" SLA checks for the maximum number of outliers based on
the mean and standard deviation of the durations. The outliers are detected
only when the total number of iterations reaches 10.

Example:
  3.1 4.2 3.6 4.5 2.8 3.3 4.1 3.8 4.3 2.9 10.2 11.2 3.4

  has 2 outliers (10.2 and 11.2), so:
    {"max_outliers": 2} -> PASS
    {"max_outliers": 1} -> FAIL

Change-Id: I7c4f77c418c7b61f71b43216110fa4c7aaccc2f5
'}, {'created': '2015-03-24 11:25:14.000000000', 'message': 'Add streaming algorithms and SLA to check for outliers

In the benchmark.processing.utils module, we add the base for the streaming
algorithms that take values from the input stream and compute certain
quantities needed for the benchmark results processing. These algorithms
should use constant memory and be able to scale.

Two streaming algorithms for computing mean and standard deviation are implemented.

There is also a new "max_outliers" SLA that checks for the maximum number of
outliers based on the mean and standard deviation of the durations, computed
using these new streaming algorithms. The outliers are detected only when the
total number of iterations reaches 10.

Example:
  3.1 4.2 3.6 4.5 2.8 3.3 4.1 3.8 4.3 2.9 10.2 11.2 3.4

  has 2 outliers (10.2 and 11.2), so:
    {"max_outliers": 2} -> PASS
    {"max_outliers": 1} -> FAIL

Change-Id: I7c4f77c418c7b61f71b43216110fa4c7aaccc2f5

commit_message:
Add streaming algorithms and SLA to check for outliers

In the common.streaming_algorithms module, we add the base for the streaming
algorithms that take values from the input stream and compute certain
quantities needed for the benchmark results processing. These algorithms
should use constant memory and be able to scale.

Two streaming algorithms for computing mean and standard deviation are implemented.

There is also a new "max_outliers" SLA that checks for the maximum number of
outliers based on the mean and standard deviation of the durations, computed
using these new streaming algorithms. By default, the outliers are detected
only when the total number of iterations reaches 10 (can be configured).

Example:
  3.1 4.2 3.6 4.5 2.8 3.3 4.1 3.8 4.3 2.9 10.2 11.2 3.4

  has 2 outliers (10.2 and 11.2), so:
    {"outliers": {"max": 2}} -> PASS
    {"outliers": {"max": 1}} -> FAIL

Bonus:
  * Add gate testing of different SLAs with the Dummy scenario
  * Add samples for all SLAs
  * Fix detailed message for max_avg_duration

Change-Id: I7c4f77c418c7b61f71b43216110fa4c7aaccc2f5

commit_message:
Replace unnecessary call to get_sync_routers

Replaces a call to get_sync_routers with a single-column
router DB query in a method that doesn't use any of the
gateway information get_sync_routers spends extra
time populating.

Change-Id: I35eae975209316aad6b2c97c909dce385729864d
Partial-Bug: #1445412

@Sean, we (IT community) have been switching from ipv4 to ipv6 for more than 10 years and most enterprise networks still don't support ipv6. commit_message:
install 'cinder-volume' package prior enabling 'cinder-volume' service

- astute deployment task enable_cinder.pp tries to start 'cinder-volume'
  service prior package 'cinder-volume' installation on Ubuntu

Change-Id: I4b233304830c28d6a6849b972ca90f9a54650b9c
Closes-bug: #1449093

commit_message:
Adding FunctionalMixin class

This is a class that implements basic unittest assert methods
and make base.Context and base.Scenario subclasses of it, so
now we can use base.assertX() methods in both classes.
This will be part of the Functional framework

Change-Id: I8e57a61ef6ec3ac0f090e3841bb9478bbc133834

commit_message:
Prohibit invalid ids in subtree and parents list

Do not allow passing invalid project_ids (None or non-existent) in
the list_project_parents() and list_projects_in_subtree() methods.

Co-Authored-By: Raildo Mascena <raildo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

commit_message:
Update tempest and AIO to test cinder backups

This commit allows tempest to be configured to test the cinder backup
service.

Additionally, we:

- add a new function to openstack_tempest_gate.sh so we can include
  some cinder-backup-related API tests in our test list
- update bootstrap-aio.sh to enable cinder backups and the ability to
  test cinder backups
- update run-tempest.sh to include the cinder backup tests in the
  default test list

Change-Id: I2b8b0255ef5fdf747bbc136c7b1152896161f8a0
Closes-Bug: #1449427
(cherry picked from commit be0169ac5b94c3c24b80d3b2176e681df57da0f7)
