commit_message:
Update cinder.conf for cinder-backup

This change updates the way we write cinder.conf when cinder backups
are enabled.  If cinder_service_backup_swift_auth is set to 'per_user',
we do not set any url/user/key/tenant options in the config.  However,
if cinder_service_backup_swift_auth is set to 'single_user' then all
auth-related options will be written.  Some additional variables were
added to allow 'single_user' to work properly.

Note that backup_swift_url is actually the swift storage URL if using
'per_user', or your auth URL if using 'single_user'.

Partial-bug: #1399386
Change-Id: Ia9d2e140d629b1f7b4c668d2f6041f3c440ab826
(cherry picked from commit e1631dbace461491c02075e1a7ff1ab1d8f4283b)
(cherry picked from commit cd9680e4ed4e7834ef6eafce6bdb0f7366e007a5)

commit_message:
Update tempest and AIO to test cinder backups

This commit allows tempest to be configured to test the cinder backup
service.

Additionally, we:

- add a new function to openstack_tempest_gate.sh so we can include
  some cinder-backup-related API tests in our test list
- update bootstrap-aio.sh to enable cinder backups and the ability to
  test cinder backups
- update run-tempest.sh to include the cinder backup tests in the
  default test list

Change-Id: I2b8b0255ef5fdf747bbc136c7b1152896161f8a0
Closes-Bug: #1449427

commit_message:
Replaces the link to Fuel plugins development documentation

Fuel Plugin Guide was removed and split into
different content pieces.
Due to this fact, we should replace plugin-dev link
with the wiki link.

Change-Id: Ic9eca612edbaf7f97b24041300d760d2429a015c
Closes-Bug: 1447025

commit_message:
Fixed Bug for KMIP Secret Storage

The KMIP secret store was incorrectly storing secrets. In some cases
this resulted in extra information being stored with the keys and in
other cases the key storage would fail with a 500 internal server
error.

This patch fixes the KMIP secret store to correctly store secrets.

Change-Id: I94944a05776d366bd33d46ddb25f7129425405d0
Co-authored-by: Kaitlin Farr <Kaitlin.Farr@jhuapl.edu>
Closes-Bug: #1449234
(cherry picked from commit 597869880f186ce951809fe85d5d7d0610f35c4f)

commit_message:
flagmappings: restore the AMQP settings split

Use multiple categories for oslo_messaging options (rpc, amqp, rabbitmq,
qpid, zmq) instead of a single rpc category.

This patch uses the autohelp script to generate tables and brings a few
other updates in the tables.

Partial-Bug: #1448119

Change-Id: I05476d97c20469c349b21404c49fccb9a9b77380

Thai,

This is a new contributor and trying to understand the workflow to use the OpenStack gerrit review system. It was my understanding that if the change is small enough and the build works, 2 core members can +2 and approve a change. It seems to me that small changes like these are easy enough to review online, especially if the outcome of the patch is better documentation and adhering to a standard that is already defined. The end result of the patch is a better doc, why continue to -1 it and send the wrong message. Maybe you can suggest for the contributor to combine the patches into 1 in the future, or supply training documentation on how to do so. Different projects have different requirements, some groups prefer small patches, how would a new contributor even know this? It’s better to encourage new contributors, to mentor them, teach them and lead instead of rejecting so quickly with very little to no explanation.'}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-04-30 09:23:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Made changes per doc conventions to 2012_2.rst

changed file to comply with official doc conventions
horizon should be lowercase per the official name
and capitalization section in the wiki
documentation conventions for OpenStack
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Conventions
Partial-bug: 1446253

Change-Id: I6cd85b12443f7dc27138cd7c2d2a7124ebeb3336

commit_message:
Wedge DB migrations if flavor migrations are not complete

In Kilo, we moved per-instance flavor information from sysmeta to a new
location. We have a lot of compatibity code as a result, which we want
to drop ASAP. In order to do that, we need to be sure that nobody can run
the post-drop code with unmigrated instances. This adds a new DB migration
that just does a sanity check and blocks moving forward if any unmigrated
instances are found.

NOTE: This does not operate on deleted instances, which matches the
behavior of the nova-manage command to push migrations.

Depends-On: Ib38f4bdb2b8e478973e0e5aaaeb4a25771af720e
Change-Id: Ide5492b8b52dec665088d7bca78c386418eba0fe

commit_message:
Replace pprint with json.dumps for --json

pprint was single-quoting things, which wasn't
making for proper json output after all.

Change-Id: I3c3fcc7d41677010593d1c8fb964d295faed45d1
Closes-Bug: #1450164

commit_message:
Added documentation on scoping of metrics, delegation and milliseconds

Closes-Bug: #1353259
* Add details on how metric is stored scoped to tenant ID

Closes-Bug: #1357182
* Specify what timestamp is in the JSON response body

Change-Id: I5535721fd501c0563aac26006d8ba543099a5993

commit_message:
Get the 'consumer' in a correct way for retyping with qos-specs

The qos specs returned from the database does not contain the
property "qos-specs". Intead, the property "consumer" can be accessed
directly.

Change-Id: I3fe57e5cc20a97d32c8b8c6089ab1e812257da45
closes-bug: #1389519
(cherry picked from commit ef59e5f8c42365f7d55ea84d4afb364241a388c3)

commit_message:
Add icmpv6 to sg_supported_protocols

support using icmpv6 (protocol num 58) in the protocol option, when creating
a security group rule.At this time, port_range_min/port_range_max represent
icmpv6 type/code, and you can use only port_range_min to specify just one type.
eg:neutron security-group-rule-create --direction ingress \
   --ethertype ipv6 --protocol icmpv6 --port-range-min 134 SECURITY_GROUP

ApiImpact
DocImpact
Partial-Bug:#1427973
Change-Id: Ide4f7476cdb8a4f04f72983917ce7dbfc7be90a5

I'm still sorta iffy on this; I understand the desire to do it but I keep on coming back to the question in the back of my mind, in that 'are we getting the most bang for the buck by doing this'? Is it ready? ...

Now I know that's hard to quantify (since my definition of bang for the buck is different than others); but knowing the state of openstack it almost feels like we should be a little bit wiser about spending our reviewer, committer ... time on something that adds a little more value to the whole code-base..."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-02-06 23:35:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

In the past, I've done detailed research on how database code, libraries, and in particular SQLAlchemy Core and ORM would be made to work with explicit async scenarios such as Twisted.  While I was very hopeful that something would be possible, it became clear that database libraries are incompatible with async systems on many levels, and that to create database abstraction layers which are would mean the production of code that is vastly less efficient and more complex in the context of Python, which despite the niceness of the "yield from" trick, really lacks native asynchronous structures as nicely as a system which does, such as Go.    So I don't have much choice but to oppose any efforts towards moving Openstack applications, either legacy or new, which are database-centric towards explicit async programming.   Applications that aren't relational database centric, such as Ceilometer with MongoDB, I don't care.  Go crazy with those.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-07 00:54:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-07 01:15:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-07 23:06:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-08 01:19:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I've spent today looking into asyncio specifically.   The situation here is definitely much better than twisted, as you can port code that is synchronous to async with this approach much more easily, b.c. you still have return values and exception catching in largely the same way (of course with a lot more machinery on top to make it work).  I am hoping that the amount of code that has to change will be lots smaller, particularly that you do have at least a shot at having a lot more intermediary functions being agnostic of whether they are invoked async or not.

Obviously I want SQLAlchemy to have an answer for asyncio, now that this specific implementation has been now "blessed", and I've begun working on the event and pool system first, this is mostly straightforward.   I would expect that all the folks working on SQLAlchemy-like systems such as aiopg would be willing to step up and provide support for these systems, as they have an interest in this story being available; support would be very helpful as these systems necessarily have to live separately from SQLA core proper (though not as far away as aiopg).

This is for pure asyncio that has "yield from", so it's python 3 only.   It also would have to provide an adapter to throw most DBAPIs into a thread pool.  This won't perform terrifically as I anticipate the overhead of movement in/out of the thread pool for every DBAPI call will be significant.   aiopg is one of the current examples of a truly async psycopg2-based DBAPI, though there are many aspects of its implementation I don't agree with.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-08 05:47:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-02-09 17:05:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'm not familiar with ceilometer design or implementation, but at least from the perspective of Nova, asyncio is a step backwards.

I'm -1 mostly because this can't be a solution for all of OpenStack."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2015-02-11 17:33:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I'm reviewing this -1 because of the underlying change here to require a conscious switch from synchronous to the explicitly asynchronous programming model.

Code that is written to be synchronous is easier to read and debug and much simpler to design. It is also (often) very hard to scale. Writing a truly asynchronous application is much more complex at all levels, to design well, to write, to understand, to debug, and to maintain. But it is so much more efficient and there is great attraction to doing this.

I've used asyncio (not with python but in C/C++) and I like it. But it is very hard to get right.

On the other hand, I entirely see the issues with eventlet; they have been a nightmare to debug (in trove) and I'd very much like to get to the bottom of some issues with it still.

That said, I'm hoping we can find a solution that will allow the programming model to remain synchronous with whatever magic under the covers and abstracted from the openstack tier.

The cost and complexity that this change (especially the let's part with eventlet) will impose on the existing code base strikes me as a huge tax."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-02-12 07:04:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-02-12 10:00:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

Is performance relevant to this discussion? My expectation (which is admittedly not supported by data) is that the cpu-bound processing of Nova is insignificant. As long as Nova can ensure the host remains IO bound, it's achieving maximum performance. Do we have any evidence that it's not doing this?

If not, then we can simplify this discussion to which is easier to write correct code for."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-02-12 10:13:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-12 15:29:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-02-12 17:18:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-02-13 15:04:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(8 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-13 16:39:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-02-16 22:25:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

On performance, Joe Gordon (amongst others) has done some profiling of basic operations, and IIRC Nova API performance is currently shockingly poor, but we don't know where the issue is yet. So performance certainly is relevant (but not dominating)."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-02-16 23:29:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I wonder if we're starting out with invalid assumptions. Reading over
the old UnifiedServiceArchitecture page in the wiki, it's not clear to
me why we felt we needed to use any special I/O handling at the
beginning of the project. This spec continues with the assumption,
substituting one tool and programming style for another.

My understanding is that asynchronous I/O techniques are usually
applied where an application is I/O-bound on several inputs or
outputs, or wants to work with many many sockets -- possibly more than
the supported number of concurrent threads that could be managed
reasonably (assuming the usual model of one thread per socket). Do we
have any components that scale that way?  Even Ceilometer, which sends
many messages about the stats it collects and consumes all of the
notifications generated by the other services and is therefore
probably the busiest user of the message bus, has been reported to be
CPU-bound rather than I/O-bound (either on itself, or the database)
and really only needs a few sockets to listen to messages and talk to
the database.

The vast majority of our services either run as a WSGI app or
communicate with the database. Some do both. Only a few agents do
neither. Any tool we choose, therefore, should work for those cases.

Web servers are the obvious place where we wouldn't be able to predict
the number of incoming requests, and where we might have a large
number of simultaneous socket connections. That makes them seem like a
good fit for asyncio. However, we've built all of our services as WSGI
apps, and so the fact that asyncio does not support WSGI (or vice
versa, depending on your perspective) is a problem.  Would we be
better served (pun not intended) to rely on stable production-ready
WSGI containers, and horizontal scaling, rather than picking up some
of the newer tools associated with asyncio?

The database driver is the other place where we do a lot of I/O and
might benefit from async, rather than blocking, I/O. However,
SQLAlchemy does not yet support asyncio (or vice versa).  While the
Ceilometer team might feel comfortable switching to an asyncio-based
Mongo driver, if there are no other such options for the rest of the
OpenStack services then we need a better picture for how we are
supposed to proceed before agreeing to go down this path.

If asyncio does not work together with WSGI or SQLAlchemy, then we
have two large blocking issues with adopting asyncio completely. We
could consider using it only where possible, but would we see enough
benefit in terms of performance or throughput in the few apps where we
could use asyncio to warrant the amount of work it would take to
modify them and support both models simultaneously?

We also have to consider how that would affect maintenance of all of
our libraries (service clients, Oslo, and third-party). We already
have some places where we have to test Oslo libraries separately with,
and without, eventlet. I don't think we want to have to do that for a
third option.

There are a few other practical considerations to a shift as big as
proposed here.

For example, discussing whether threading or asyncio is "easier" to
use is largely subjective. When eventlet was selected the developer
pool was significantly smaller than it is now, and I'm not sure
everyone agreed completely on the choice at the time. We're unlikely
to find the community agreeing completely on that point today, so we
need to look seriously at the amount of work involved in any change
this big, and weigh that cost against the benefits.

Given the issues with libraries supporting asyncio, a more objective
question is "How many of the tools and libraries we are already using
support the proposed approach?" For example, we have encountered some
libraries that do not work well with eventlet, and we have pointed to
cases where techniques and libraries we use do not work with
asyncio. Do we rely on any libraries that are not thread-safe?

A common complaint with threading is deadlocks due to accessing global
state. From what I've seen, most of our global state is kept in the
database, rather than in-memory data structures, because we're already
dealing with distributed services and "eventual consistency". How
often do we keep global state in memory in an application in a way
that would be affected by concurrency changes -- where would we need
to add new locking code if we switch to threads, for example?

We have several places where we use green threads, often explicitly,
and rely on eventlet's to patch the threading module so the locking
classes work. Assuming that code is correct now, would we expect it to
function correctly under regular threads (if we do not let eventlet
monkey patch)?

Another consideration is how much we would need to change the
application code. One reason eventlet was appealing was that code
using eventlet looks synchronous, even though it often ends up running
differently when executed. Explicit async code needs to be changed in
a few ways, as you describe in the spec. Would we need to make similar
changes for threading? For example, we might need to add locks in
places where eventlet is protecting us today. Is there any way to
predict what other changes might be needed, without doing a full
analysis of the OpenStack code base (which I'm definitely not asking
for)?

To sum up: I'm not sure we need to worry as much about asynchronous
I/O as we are. If I remember correctly, we originally started
discussing asyncio as an alternative to eventlet in the context of
porting OpenStack, and especially oslo.messaging, to Python 3, rather
than doing it for its own sake. While eventlet's support for Python 3
is improving, it's not 100% yet, and that is not the only motivation
we have for dropping it. Perhaps we should reframe this discussion in
terms of "moving away from eventlet" instead of "moving to" a specific
solution to give more attention to some of the alternatives in light
of the practical considerations I've mentioned above.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-02-17 14:02:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

"The database driver is the other place where we do a lot of I/O and might benefit from async, rather than blocking, I/O. However, SQLAlchemy does not yet support asyncio (or vice versa)."

According to Mike's benchmark, it's faster to run DB queries in threads than running them asynchronously using asyncio:
http://techspot.zzzeek.org/2015/02/15/asynchronous-python-and-databases/

I propose to *combine* the nice asyncio syntax for coroutines with a pool of threads for DB queries (using loop.run_in_executor()). In this case, SQLAchemy doesn't have to be modified at all.

As any other blocking functions called with loop.run_in_executor(). I suggest this option for any function which may block the event loop for "too long" (ex: more than 1 ms), especially I/O operations.


"If asyncio does not work together with WSGI or SQLAlchemy, then we have two large blocking issues with adopting asyncio completely."

I chose to put WSGI outside the spec. There *are* solutions to use WSGI with asyncio, but they require hacks like monkey-patching, or modifying the code (I don't know how exactly, sorry). I prefer to focus first on asyncio, to check if it fits into OpenStack, so then see if it's worth to investigate the WSGI issue.

"We could consider using it only where possible, but would we see enough benefit in terms of performance or throughput in the few apps where we could use asyncio to warrant the amount of work it would take to modify them and support both models simultaneously?"

Performances are not my primary motivation, it's more to have more reliable code with a nice syntax. If the code runs faster, it would be a nice side effect. According to comments, OpenStack doesn't fit into the asyncio ideal use case (a lot of idle sockets like web sockets) where asyncio can be expected to be much faster. By the way, asyncio is based on an event loop, as eventlet. So there is no huge difference between eventlet and asyncio in term of internal design. It's more differences in the way to use them.


"We also have to consider how that would affect maintenance of all of our libraries (service clients, Oslo, and third-party). We already have some places where we have to test Oslo libraries separately with, and without, eventlet. I don't think we want to have to do that for a third option."

I understood that most OpenStack people want to replace eventlet with something else. Somewhere, we have to invest energy to fix the eventlet issue, no? I don't understand the logic. 

In short, you choose to keep eventlet with its known issues?

eventlet looks to be an expensive technical debt in OpenStack, no?


"we need to look seriously at the amount of work involved in any change this big, and weigh that cost against the benefits."

In most comments, I read something like *all* OpenStack code must be fully rewritten from scratch to put "yield from" *everywhere*.

I checked asyncio source code. asyncio must use yield-from everywhere since all code must be asynchronous (which is not the case for OpenStack where blocking function calls are acceptable).

The development version of asyncio has 11,006 lines. Only 94 lines contains "yield from": 0.8%. (To be honest, I had to double check. I was surprised by this low number :-))


> "How many of the tools and libraries we are already using support the proposed approach?"
> For example, we have encountered some libraries that do not work well with eventlet,
> and we have pointed to cases where techniques and libraries we use do not work with asyncio.

Remember that OpenStack uses eventlet with monkey-patching. A very few number libraries are prepared for monkey-patching. I'm suprised that it works so well :-) As I wrote in the spec, most eventlet issues come from the monkey-patching, not from asynchronous programming (green threads).


> Do we rely on any libraries that are not thread-safe?

The principle of asyncio is to run all code in a single thread. In this case, no lock is needed ;-)

*If* you choose to run code in a dedicated (pool of) thread(s), you control which functions are called in a thread. If needed, you may put locks on functions which are not thread-safe.

Later, you may enhance these libraries to add a builtin ayncio support, or make them thread-safe, if you like.

Again, we don't know which libraries *must* be called in threads for performances. So it's difficult to estimate the amount of work to use them correctly.


> where would we need to add new locking code if we switch to threads, for example?

I cannot answer. I don't know if locks are missing.

I hope that no new lock is need ;-) I'm not sure that all issues will be seen with asyncio if most of the code run in a single thread.


> We have several places where we use green threads, often explicitly, and rely on eventlet's to patch the threading module so the locking classes work. Assuming that code is correct now, would we expect it to function correctly under regular threads (if we do not let eventlet monkey patch)?

I have the same question. I expect some issues from @oslo_concurrency.lock_utils.lock or @oslo_concurrency.lock_utils.synchronized. I'm not sure that these decorators were already well tested with native threads. If there are issues with these two decorators, I expect that it should be easy to fix them.

I checked ceilometer: lockutils doesn't look to be used. ceilometer/openstack/common/lockutils.py exists, but I don't see it used outside tests.


> Another consideration is how much we would need to change the application code. One reason eventlet was appealing was that code using eventlet looks synchronous, even though it often ends up running differently when executed.

If you take blocking code and run it in asyncio: it just works. Blocking functions will block a few milliseconds, that's all.

If you want better performances, enable asyncio debug mode: it will warn you if a function blocks longer than 100 ms. You can tune the threshold (100 ms) to detect more blocking calls.

See:
https://docs.python.org/dev/library/asyncio-dev.html#debug-mode-of-asyncio
and
https://docs.python.org/dev/library/asyncio-dev.html#handle-blocking-functions-correctly


> Explicit async code needs to be changed in a few ways, as you describe in the spec.
> Would we need to make similar changes for threading?
> For example, we might need to add locks in places where eventlet is protecting us
> today.

Hum, I'm not aware of eventlet protections. What are these protections? What I understood is that basically green threads are similar to threads: a green thread can be interrupted anywhere. So code running in green threads must be "thread-safe" (green thread safe? :-)). Concurrency issues already exist with eventlet.

So I understand that existing race conditions were already fixed. No?

asyncio may "hide" more issues than eventlet since there are less places where your code may be interrupted (ex: at exactly 94 lines in asyncio). I don't know if it's correct to say that asyncio hides issues, since there are no more issues.

Well, let's take a dummy example:

    def unsafe_method(self):
        unique_id = self.data['id']
        maybe_async_func()
        self.data['id'] += 1
        return unique_id

Using eventlet, you don't know if maybe_async_func() may pause unsafe_method(), in which case unsafe_method() can be called again from a different green thread => race condition.


Unsafe asyncio version:

    def unsafe_method(self):
        unique_id = self.data['id']
        yield from always_async_func()
        self.data['id'] += 1
        return unique_id

=> there is an obvious race condition: "yield from" interrupts unsafe_method(), so you may get the same identifier twice. You need a lock to protect self.data or write the code differently (ex: increment id before calling the second function).

Using asyncio, you must use "yield from" if the second function is asynchronous. There is not "maybe" async function. A function is always or never asynchronous.

Now, let's say that the second function is not asynchronous:

    def unsafe_method(self):
        unique_id = self.data['id']
        sync_func()
        self.data['id'] += 1
        return unique_id

In this case, you can only have a race condition if sync_func() calls again unsafe_method(), directly or indirectly. It's less likely since we don't pass self to sync_func().

As I wrote in the spec: asyncio only reduces the risk of race condition, insane code like reentrant and recursive function calls can still have race conditions ;-)

Note: if sync_func() schedules a call to unsafe_method() using call_soon() or a coroutine, the scheduled call will only be called "later", after unsafe_method() exited since unsafe_method() cannot wake up the event loop (there is no yield-from).


> Perhaps we should reframe this discussion in terms of "moving away from eventlet" instead of "moving to" a specific solution to give more attention to some of the alternatives in light of the practical considerations I've mentioned above.

This spec helped to evaluate the thread option. Do you see more alternatives?

If someone is motivated to replace eventlet with threads, it would be better to write a new spec. I didn't investigated the thread option, I only summarized comments.

I don't like threads, especially in Python, I prefer to stay away from them ;-)'}, {'account_id': 100, 'date': '2015-02-17 17:14:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

> I understood that most OpenStack people want to replace eventlet with something else. Somewhere, we have to invest energy to fix the eventlet issue, no? I don't understand the logic.
> In short, you choose to keep eventlet with its known issues?
> eventlet looks to be an expensive technical debt in OpenStack, no?

I think you are misinterpting peoples dislike for this proposal as liking eventlet. No one likes eventlet :)

Just that some people don't see asyncio as a significantly better solution than asyncio.

In some ways it's worse. It requires a ton of gratuitous syntax changes. The claims that explicitly asynchronous helps prevent bugs falls flat in the face of our existing parallelism."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-02-17 17:40:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Feel free to do it on a long running branch, I just want the branch that I'm watching to be focused on a relatively small surface area.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-02-23 14:02:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-02-25 03:19:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

So, I'm glad you've written this up.

Its not at all clear to me that the previous learning curve issues that broke the use of Twisted will be better with asyncio; further I think the issues with threaded code are being oversold: there are ways to write bad things in many contexts, but our code is primarily interacting with external resources - so local context, no in-process global state is the rule, not the exception.

I like asyncio per se, and its in the Python space a fairly good approximation to communicating sequential processes, but something like https://code.google.com/p/pycsp/wiki/Getting_Started_With_PyCSP or http://goless.readthedocs.org/en/latest/ is perhaps more general and targetted directly at that design pattern (http://golang.org/doc/faq#csp) which is one of the selling points proponents of golang put forward.

Right now our programming model is 'threads, with eventlet magic'; if we're going to move off of that, I think genuine threads is the lowest sized delta, with anything explicit - CSP, asyncioor Twisted all being a larger delta.

In terms of choosing what framework / design we should aim for, Glyph's post about non-local reasoning is nice, but I think it ignores the fact that both Twisted and asyncio are very non-local in  nature - they both perform unsafe operations in-line with business logic, and that's a recipe for having weird-ass exceptions propogating up through fairly arbitrary code paths. Explicit CSP eases this, since rather than deep exceptions you have explicit layers between the processes. Of course, WSGI doesn't do a super job of supporting CSP, 

With Python 3 support in eventlet now we don't have any particular urgency for revising things, but if we are changing things my preferences would be:
 - full blown CSP, probably through the goless library
 - regular threads / multiprocess
 - asyncio/trollius/twisted

Because:
 - (CSP > asyncio) channels are really quite different to the coroutine approach asyncio uses (you can buffer, you can force a particular channel into one direction rather than bidirectional, you can select on multiple channels to get the next actual output whereas using iterators you have to suspend on just one at a time).
 - (CSP > threads) CSP abstractions are more capable than threads (though we could in principle write shims - indeed, thats what goless gives you...)
 - (threads > asyncio) our code is currently written in threaded style, and I don't think the benefits (though there are some indeed) from asyncio is worth a full-code-base rewrite. CSP offers enough on top of that to make it worth it IMNSHO."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-02-26 15:31:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ideally this would merge with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/156711/ in a meta-spec to present a common overview of the problem, a list of potential solutions with their benefit and drawbacks -- then we can pick one option and have all the alternatives we rejected properly documented. That may avoid to come back to it next month.

I'd also like an assessment of the work required by each option, as well as some performance data (in the spirit of http://techspot.zzzeek.org/2015/02/15/asynchronous-python-and-databases/)"}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2015-03-04 00:02:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-23 11:44:29.000000000', 'message': '[IBP] Fix ValueError while parsing: mdadm --detail

fuel-agent doesn't expect header from 'mdadm --detail' output where
'State' is not present.

fuel-agent should expect 2 types of headers:
" Number Major Minor RaidDevice State\n" (already supported)
" Number Major Minor RaidDevice\n" - addressed by this patch.

This patch is required to let fuel-agent consume both types of headers.

Additionally fuel-agent will start to log 'mdadm --detail' output to ease
troubleshooting.

Change-Id: Ie20db2c14bdc5669566a140a34d63d28c6115d11
Closes-Bug: #1446186

commit_message:
[IBP] Fix ValueError while parsing: mdadm --detail

fuel-agent doesn't expect header from 'mdadm --detail' output where
'State' is not present.

fuel-agent should expect 2 types of headers:
" Number Major Minor RaidDevice State\n" (already supported)
" Number Major Minor RaidDevice\n" - addressed by this patch.

This patch is required to let fuel-agent consume both types of headers.

Additionally fuel-agent will start to log 'mdadm --detail' output to ease
troubleshooting.

Change-Id: Ie20db2c14bdc5669566a140a34d63d28c6115d11
Closes-Bug: #1446186

Hi Martin,

This looks good. Stylistically we are trying to do as much of the configuration via hiera however. So instead of using a 'class' in the module we would prefer to just use an 'include ::heat:;keystone::foo' instead. For the auth_url parameter you'll need to use a list_join function in the Heat template. A good example of how to do that is here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/162284/

For all the static settings you can just put those into the puppet-controller.yaml heat template's mapped_data section and add your comment about removing them when we switch to Keystone V3 there perhaps."}, {'account_id': 5241, 'date': '2015-03-09 10:11:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-09 10:11:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

The CI failure appears to be valid. Looking at the os-collect-config log on the controller node I see:

Error: heat-keystone-setup-domain &>/dev/null returned 1 instead of one of [0]\u001b[0m\n\u001b[1;31mError: /Stage[main]/Heat::Keystone::Domain/Exec[heat_domain_create]/returns: change from notrun to 0 failed: heat-keystone-setup-domain &>/dev/null returned 1 instead of one of [0]\u001b[0m\n\u001b[1;31mWarning: /Stage[main]/Heat::Keystone::Domain/Heat_domain_id_setter[heat_domain_id]: Skipping because of failed...

Should we skip the include if the heat keystone password is not set (the default)?'}, {'account_id': 5241, 'date': '2015-03-12 12:42:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-12 12:42:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/79/160279/6/check/noop/f373907/ : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 5241, 'date': '2015-03-12 12:53:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Moved static data to Hiera. Regarding Heat Keystone password, I thought that it is generated and saved as env OVERCLOUD_HEAT_PASSWORD from where it is then loaded to Heat template. I think that it would be better to use generated password in case it is not set ... or am I confused here?'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-03-12 13:49:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

> Should we skip the include if the heat keystone password is not set (the default)?

IMO no, the empty string default is wrong - ideally we would never specify a default in the template for a password which is supposed to be random (or at least, provided by the user) - e.g "unset" isn't much better, because we'll silently use a bad password if the user forgets to pass one as a parameter.

Either way, I think if an option to not configure the heat domain is desired, a boolean would be a better way. commit_message:
Keystone domain for Heat

This patch adds support for configuring Keystone domain for Heat
via heat-keystone-setup-domain script. It should be reverted
as soon as Keystone v3 is fully functional.

Change-Id: I7397f49fac17c30262d02b70021d613aef5c6cad

commit_message:
Move the manually-generated XML table file

cinder-netapp_cdot_extraspecs.xml is not autogenerated and I often end
up deleting it while working on the config-reference. Having it moved to
another directory should make things a little less painful.

This function will be used within the TripleO puppet implementation

'}]
commit_message:
Add find_bind_ip function

This patch adds a custom Puppet function called find_bind_ip.
This function will be used within the TripleO puppet implementation
to help obtain the correct local bind IP for a provided subnet.

The goal is to better integrate with network architectures which
isolate traffic on different networks.

Change-Id: Ifd448ae0909aee538a7068d0b8ac6441a9e51872

commit_message:
add source_quiet function

sourcing a file under xtrace causes a huge amount of gorp in the
console, and it's rarely useful. Create a source_quiet to source
things with tracing turned off.

Change-Id: Ic0569d78314b85a8a7dab028e5895db8f37bc30e

Code improvement: avoid reduntant if conditions

while adopting stack, the presence of adopt-data
is being checked twice, which can be done with
only once.

[{'created': '2015-04-29 08:57:23.000000000', 'message': "Update cinder.conf for cinder-backup

This change updates the way we write cinder.conf when cinder backups
are enabled so that we default to not specifying a backup_swift_url.
This results in cinder-backup obtaining swift_url from the
environment which avoids the need for the deployer to specify if they
have a swift installation in their environment.

We also only write backup_swift_user/backup_swift_key to cinder.conf
when cinder_service_backup_swift_auth is set to 'single_user', as they
are not used when backup_swift_auth is set to 'per_user'.

Partial-bug: #1399386
Change-Id: Ia9d2e140d629b1f7b4c668d2f6041f3c440ab826

This change updates the way we write cinder.conf when cinder backups
are enabled.  If cinder_service_backup_swift_auth is set to 'per_user',
we do not set any url/user/key/tenant options in the config.  However,
if cinder_service_backup_swift_auth is set to 'single_user' then all
auth-related options will be written.  Some additional variables were
added to allow 'single_user' to work properly.

Note that backup_swift_url is actually the swift storage URL if using
'per_user', or your auth URL if using 'single_user'.

commit_message:
Update cinder.conf for cinder-backup

This change updates the way we write cinder.conf when cinder backups
are enabled.  If cinder_service_backup_swift_auth is set to 'per_user',
we do not set any url/user/key/tenant options in the config.  However,
if cinder_service_backup_swift_auth is set to 'single_user' then all
auth-related options will be written.  Some additional variables were
added to allow 'single_user' to work properly.

Note that backup_swift_url is actually the swift storage URL if using
'per_user', or your auth URL if using 'single_user'.

Partial-bug: #1399386
Change-Id: Ia9d2e140d629b1f7b4c668d2f6041f3c440ab826

commit_message:
Force IPv4 settings for APT

* Create /etc/apt/apt.conf.d/05disable-ipv6 and set Acquire::ForceIPv4 "true";
  to disable IPv6 as Ubuntu DNS returns IPv6 sometimes.
* Delete the same part from fuel_agent_ci cloud-init template as it should be
  configured by Orchestrator

Change-Id: I90fe58157c3eac04842102b1cb956bbeb324413a
Closes-Bug: 1450004
Signed-off-by: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovatiuk@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Parse Bridge Mappings to include XAG

The pypowervm library recently defaulted the XAG attribute (extended
attributes) to none.  The side effect to this is that the VIOS read is
no longer returning the Shared Ethernet Adapters.

This change updates the parse of the bridge mappings to pass in the
appropriate XAG to get the proper return data.

It also includes a unit test for the parse_bridge_mappings which had
been missed initially.

Change-Id: Ifb9ce3b9c008cf71715667d22312b8fa6a87304a

commit_message:
Use ipv4 address for connectivity in lb integration test

You can not specify subnet for a server creation. Therefore server
nic would get ip adresses from all subnets. We should pick the
ipv4 address to check connectivity.

Also added change to NovaClientPlugin to provide ipv4 address.

Change-Id: I2eb3bdb359aca0cfaebf0be98db79170c681a078
Closes-Bug: #1450293

commit_message:
Pacemaker fixes for controller add/remove

* Location constraint should be present for
  a pacemaker service to be started even if
  this service is actually started.

* pcmk_nodes resource to add and remove
  corosync nodes

Change-Id: I97035e633c33f94519b66526268620f9cd6cc958
Closes-Bug: 1394188

commit_message:
RN6.0-updates2 Neutron resolved issues

Adds Neutron-related resolved issues:
-Neutron loses connection to rabbitmq with Errno 32.
-No connectivity to instances in HA neutron env.
-Security group listing operation fails with timeout.
-Neutron server creates more than one port for a VM.
-Incorrect exception reference in ml2 plugin.
-Neutron server consumes redundant resources.
-Neutron port is not found exception.
-Performance improvement of sec groups RPC-related code.
-radvd >= 2.0 blocks router update processing.

Change-Id: Ic84a961ab1dd64024d069fb79efb27a4aa204150

commit_message:
Update ironic config tables for kilo

Updated ironic.headers and regenerated/updated the config tables
for ironic, using stable/kilo branch. Deleted tables that aren't
used by ironic (most likely due to some bug when generating these
with authohelp-wrapper having the venvs of all the OpenStack
projects).

I created and generated the config tables via
 "./autohelp-wrapper -b stable/kilo create ironic" and
 "./autohelp-wrapper -f docbook ironic".

Change-Id: I95644482b107a3f71962bc52618dcd5a6ff597af

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-30 08:06:28.000000000', 'message': 'Remove DVR gw router SNAT redirect only if device exists

L3 service plugin first calls to remove_router_interface from the L2 OVS agent
which delete this port from OVS and then the service plugin calls
to remove the router interface from L3 agent.

This check ensure that the L3 agent will not try to remove the device
gateway direction if the device no longer exists
(Happens when the router external gateway is removed)
(See bug for more details)

Closes-Bug: #1435012
Change-Id: Ieeaa01e7c0393f5200d1a8d2bbbc16befe7699a2

commit_message:
Suppress exception when trying to remove non existing device in SNAT redirect

L3 service plugin first calls to remove_router_interface from the L2 OVS agent
which delete this port from OVS and then the service plugin calls
to remove the router interface from L3 agent.

Catch the exception thrown on the delete gateway, if its due to device doesn't exists
ignore the exception

Closes-Bug: #1435012
Change-Id: Ieeaa01e7c0393f5200d1a8d2bbbc16befe7699a2

commit_message:
Honor shared storage on resize revert

This patch improves the logic in resize_revert() to properly honor
shared storage when destroying the unneeded instance.  In the case of
shared storage, the disks need not be destroyed and doing so results in
the inability to start the original instance.

Conflicts is caused by moving tests to /unit directory

Also commit contains squash from fixed implementation of determening
if storage is shared (get from commit fde77d49ff550b73f5f1671edc7366c9b7646200)

Conflicts:
        nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute.py
        nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute_mgr.py

Closes-Bug: #1399244
Change-Id: I310f6b62a790e4549a2cf9ff3842655da552177a
(cherry picked from commit eec0937af9d88f3c7ffacf9ce7b8955b2e4be479)

commit_message:
Replace plugin tests to another test group

Changes:
1) Replace plugin tests to another test group
2) Fix doc string for example plugin
3) Add exit statement when plugin couldn't be enabled
   to all plugin tests

Change-Id: Ia3802fbda36c1a857764945721964274770cc464
Closes-bug: #1447158
Closes-bug: #1447239

commit_message:
Fix fedora kernel install in ibp mode

Now, when we select Image based provisioning (ibp) and also
select install Fedora kernel it installs old CentOS kernel.

Install both kernels on images and then choose right
kernel (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/176864/)

Change-Id: Ib3a269562fb44f65ba1fb59861707e71627d17c8
Partially-closes-bug: #1398643

commit_message:
Fix exec resource ensurability for auxiliary repos

Dependence on part of the files created by the exec
statements in nailgun::auxiliaryrepos was inadequate
to work with patching tests. Now replaced with unless
statements to ensure all files and directories.

Release file is now set to replace => false.

Change-Id: I3fe15130d3c70ab4441b7fe9e3b108f617738cc8
Closes-Bug: #1450124

commit_message:
Load archive_policy named resource metric

If the orm object of a metric is loaded with a resource,
the joinedload of the resource doesn't include the archive_policy.

This change load the archive_policy when we ask for a metric attached
to a resource.

Closes-bug: #1449452
Change-Id: Ic48f43048fe3e14b42b347cf44250183de60f9d8
(cherry picked from commit c3660930ff45fc5175032294836784417f0ea306)

[{'created': '2015-04-29 14:00:32.000000000', 'message': 'ceilometer: Use http session in dispatcher

The ceilometer dipatcher needs to do between 2 to 5 http requests
for each samples. Current it use the basic API of the python-requests
library, that creates 1 tcp connections for each http requests.
Connections are pooled by default (10 simultaneous connections) and
a error is raised when the pool is exhausted.

This change move to the session API of python-requests to
creates only one tcp connection per ceilometer-collector workers,
and block when the pool exhausts.

Change-Id: I8255622cf57082785b48754d9e506413ee9122a7
(cherry picked from commit 40bea729120b536aaff52019189dd8cc48d46f2e)
'}]
commit_message:
ceilometer: Use http session in dispatcher

The ceilometer dipatcher needs to do between 2 to 5 http requests
for each samples. Current it use the basic API of the python-requests
library, that creates 1 tcp connections for each http requests.
Connections are pooled by default (10 simultaneous connections) and
a error is raised when the pool is exhausted.

This change move to the session API of python-requests to
creates only one tcp connection per ceilometer-collector workers,
and block when the pool exhausts.

Change-Id: I8255622cf57082785b48754d9e506413ee9122a7
(cherry picked from commit 40bea729120b536aaff52019189dd8cc48d46f2e)

commit_message:
Switch to Hacking 0.9.x

The newer hacking version for Juno introduces a newer version of
pep8 checks that check for:

 E265 block comment should start with '# '
 E251 unexpected spaces around keyword / parameter equals

and has a few bugfixes over the previous version, so it catches
more pep8 violations. Those occurrences are fixed alongway.

The following new Hacking 0.9x check was fixed alongway:

* Group third-party and site-packages in one group of imports

The following new Hacking 0.9x checks are blacklisted for now:

 H305  imports not grouped correctly
 H405  multi line docstring summary not separated with an empty line
 H904  Wrap long lines in parentheses instead of a backslash

They can be cleaned up in later commits.

Change-Id: Icc2f8fc868aad2ea8eaca1fe5a6175aa4a950a23

commit_message:
Remove width parameter from rst markup

Using :width: parameter for changing screenshots
size is incorrect: they should be scaled up
with css style instead.

This commit removes :width: from all sections related to
VMware.

Change-Id: I8c2634693452f2adfa19858889d5d4b90e119c2e
Related-Bug: 1449877

commit_message:
Skip ruby21, ruby-2.1.1 during bootstrap operation

Because of the shift of ruby-2.1 to ruby21
package naming, the ruby21 package should be
excluded as for ruby-2.1.1 during bootstrap

Change-Id: I86c8f7b07f3b94481a932a5456b112fc32adf27a

commit_message:
Installation version info added into stats protocol

For handling filtration of data on the collector side we introduce
installation_version into stats saving protocol. Installation version
is dictionary with 'release' and 'build_id' values.
Function fuel_release_info moved from installation_info to statistics.utils.

Change-Id: I1259aaae86464aab5923a0caa36c75cbe99c3e58
Partial-Bug: #1443347

For more details on this and other bugs, please see http://status.openstack.org/elastic-recheck/"}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-04-08 12:55:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

So I have some issues with the commit message and it's formatting, which I'd appreciate some cleanup on. (although if we get ready to land it I won't block on that, I'd probably just fix it myself)

But, my bigger concern is with the implication of this patch. If the behavior was what this patch is claiming to fix (that the snapshots need to be completely removed before we can delete it's parent volume) then I would expect us to be hitting the delete race quite frequently in the gate. But to my knowledge we've not seen it once.

My gut feeling here is that there is a bug around this depending on the cinder configuration or backend driver. Before we land this I want to see where this race is coming from in cinder. If it's just a per backend issue (in other words lvm lets you delete a volume right after just issuing a snapshot delete, but ceph doesn't) then I would argue this is actually a cinder issue which must be fixed first. I'd rather not mask over a bug like this if it is in fact differences depending on cinder configuration."}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-04-08 13:59:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-08 15:02:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@matthew,
   Cinder fs-backed driver (eg: glusterfs) doesn't allow to delete a volume if it has a snap (since the way snaps are implemented using qcow2 files, it won't make sense to delete
volume with the snap dangling around)

Secondly, i think (maybe) why this issue hasn't seen much
is because this testcase was disabled in cinder, until 
recently when the LVM backend issue was fixed.

@Yaroslav,
  Pls see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171597/2
I think the right way is to delete the snapshot before
shutting down the instances. That solves multiple issues:
1) No race condition
2) fs-backed cinder drivers needs snaps to be deleted before
volume can be deleted, so this makes race go away
3) Most imp.ly patch 171597 ensures that fs-backed drivers
who use hypervisor assisted snapshot feature, the only way
to delete snapshot is when Instance (server) is active, so
this testcase anyways fails for gluster cinder driver
because it is not able to delete the snap after shutting
down the instance, since hypervisor doesn't allow that
to happen

So if you agree, i hope the patch @ 171597 solves this patch
issue as well, so we abandon this patch and go with
171597 ?"}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-04-09 01:22:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

So Cinder is in fact set such that Volumes can not be deleted if there are any outstanding snapshots, we've enforced that since day one.  The race here is specific to Gluster in this case as I'm unaware of any other drivers encountering this "race" as you put it.  

As noted in the bug, it would be really great if you could include a link to an actual gate run.  That way others including myself can actually look at the logs and have a better understanding of what's going on including driver information.

I'm concerned that Gluster seems to be the only device that I've heard is having this issue, and as such I'm reluctant to make changes to the test without having a better understanding of the failure.  In other words, I'm concerned that we're masking an issue with the Gluster backend itself.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-04-09 01:26:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Ahh... even better, looks like the root of this is fixed here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171482/'}, {'account_id': 14428, 'date': '2015-04-09 06:10:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@John,

Earlier in GlusterFS case, "test_volume_boot_pattern" is failing because of two reasons:
1. Provider location is not present for the newly created volume
2. Trying to delete the snapshot when VM is in SHUTOFF state.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171482/ solves the first issue.

In GlusterFS, when we want to delete Snapshot VM should be in Running state. Please have a look at the logs [1].

Later I sent a another patch [2] to delete the snapshot before SHUTTING DOWN the VM.

[1] http://logs.openstack.org/82/171482/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full-glusterfs-nv/2291eea/
[2] https://review.openstack.org/171597'}, {'account_id': 14428, 'date': '2015-04-09 06:14:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Jhon,

Please have a look at below link for more details.
http://logs.openstack.org/82/171482/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full-glusterfs-nv/2291eea/logs/screen-n-cpu.txt.gz?#_2015-04-08_20_23_58_257'}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-09 07:07:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@John,
  As you said above and I quote:

"So Cinder is in fact set such that Volumes can not be deleted if there are any outstanding snapshots,"

which means all snaps should be deleted before volume is
deleted. Per the info provided in this patch, the author is
clearly stating that addCleanup_with_wait is async hence
sometimes it causes the volume to be deleted before snap,
causing cinder excp, hence failing the testcase.

If the above is correct, isn't this patch valid and genuine ?

Reg. gluster failure, pls see the thread @
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-April/060983.html

Gluster error is because, the tempest testcase shuts down
the instances and then tries to delete snap which is not
supported yet by nova/libvirt. Most other drivers of
cinder do not go to nova as they can handle snaps on the
backend, but glusterfs (and in future nfs) can't hence the
issue. Once we get past this issue, I think we will hit
the issue for which this patch is sent,if the race between
volume delete and snap delete is happening.'}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-04-09 15:14:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Guys,

1. I don't use GlusteFS as Cinder Backend. I use LVM.
2. I really don't understand why these tests have success on gate runs? As far as I understand, LVM is used as Cinder Backend on gate. Or not?
3. Could anyone explain to me, it is a valid test case to delete the volume snapshot and right after that delete the volume, not waiting for the snapshot deletion? If it is a valid test case, I should abandon this patch and fix the issue in another place. Probably, in the configuration of Cinder or LVM. According to John's message 

>>So Cinder is in fact set such that Volumes can not be deleted if there are any outstanding snapshots, we've enforced that since day one.
<<

the described test case is not valid. Right? In this case this patch makes sense."}, {'account_id': 14428, 'date': '2015-04-09 16:33:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Yaroslav Lobankov,

Let me try to clarify:
1. When we use LVM we can't find this issue. It occurs only when we use GlusterFS as Cinder backend. This is because GlusterFS (is the only driver) uses nova (libvirt) to create/delete online snapshots and libvirt doesn't have support to delete snapshot when VM is in SHUTOFF state.

2. Yes on gate jobs lvm is the default backend, so we can't see the issue there. But "check-tempest-dsvm-full-glusterfs-nv" is failing because it uses GlusterFS as Cinder backend.

3. Existing test case is valid, It do "ShutDown VMs" -> "Delete Snapshot" -> "Delete Volume"
This works for all drivers except GlusterFS, as I said in poinrt #1.

In GlusterFS we need flow like "Delete Snapshot" -> "Shutdown VMs" -> "Delete Volume" (This flow works for all drivers including GlusterFS).

You are absolutely correct, Volume can't be deleted, when we have outstanding snapshots.'}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-04-09 17:16:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Bharat Kumar Kobagana, thanks for your clarification.

>>1. When we use LVM we can't find this issue.

I am constantly hitting this issue when I use LVM as Cinder Backend. 

It is worth noting this patch is not intended to set right cleanup order. This patch is intended to wait for complete deletion of the volume snapshot before we start to delete the volume. As you said, we cannot delete the volume when we have outstanding snapshots. So shouldn't we wait for complete deletion of the volume snapshot before deleting the volume?"}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-10 05:15:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@yaroslav,
  As i said in my prev comment (see above) that this patch looks genuine to me, but we don't see this issue when we use
LVM backend in our local setup. Also I am not tempest
expert to really confirm that addCleanup_with_wait does NOT
wait for snap to be deleted before volume is deleted.

Assuming that is the case, I feel this patch is correct, since
per Cinder one cannot delete the volume before snaps are deleted

What that brings up the Q is why the dsvm-full CI job
that uses the LVM backend doesn't see this issue and why
only its seen in your enviorment ?"}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-04-10 08:10:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Deepak,

>>What that brings up the Q is why the dsvm-full CI job that uses the LVM backend doesn't see this issue and why only its seen in your enviorment ?

I think it may be related to using Devstack. I use Fuel to deploy an OpenStack cluster. My OpenStack cluster has 1 controller and 1 compute. The controller is a virtual machine, the compute is a hardware server.

Method addCleanup_with_wait(...) does not wait for complete resource deletion right after sending the request to delete resource.

Guys, please, take a look at method _create_volume_from_snapshot(...). This method uses another method create_volume(...) that is defined in ScenarioTest class. Pay attention, method create_volume(...) has such a parameter as "wait_on_delete" and the default value of this parameter is True. If you take a look at this method more attentively, you will see this piece of code http://paste.openstack.org/show/201813/ . I am trying to do the same thing.'}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-04-10 09:44:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-04-10 09:44:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-04-10 09:44:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Patch Set 4 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-04-10 10:00:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-10 11:13:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

[{'created': '2015-04-08 10:55:24.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing race condition in test "test_volume_boot_pattern"

In file tempest/scenario/test_volume_boot_pattern.py
there is a method for creating snapshots from volumes.
The method is _create_snapshot_from_volume(...) and
it is used in test "test_volume_boot_pattern".
The thing is that _create_snapshot_from_volume(...)
uses method self.addCleanup_with_wait(...) in order
to delete created volume snapshot after test finished
(https://github.com/openstack/tempest/blob/master/tempest/scenario/test_volume_boot_pattern.py#L74-78).
The use of self.addCleanup_with_wait(...) sometimes
causes failure of test "test_volume_boot_pattern"
(http://paste.openstack.org/show/200251/ ). Thus we
have a race condition. If volume snapshot is already
deleted when deleting volume, the test will have success.
If volume snapshot is not deleted when deleting volume,
the test will fail.

Change-Id: I11207c3ac9296389c5e195b2296fc47e65a7486c
Closes-Bug: #1441563

commit_message:
Wait for complete deletion of volume snapshot before deleting volume

In file tempest/scenario/test_volume_boot_pattern.py there 
is a method for creating snapshots from volumes. The method 
is _create_snapshot_from_volume(...). The thing is that method
_create_snapshot_from_volume(...) uses method 
self.addCleanup_with_wait(...) (that does not wait for complete 
resource deletion right after sending the request to delete the 
resource) in order to delete created volume snapshot after the test
finished. But volumes cannot be deleted when there are outstanding 
snapshots. Therefore we should wait for complete deletion of 
the volume snapshot before we start to delete the volume.

Closes-Bug: #1441563

Change-Id: I11207c3ac9296389c5e195b2296fc47e65a7486c

commit_message:
Make mongodb retrieve conf from proper file

Currently mongodb is reading file from /etc/mongodb.conf (default when
package was coming from OSP), a recent change in EPEL mongodb package made
it supersed the version from OSP. In this version, it reads its default
configuration from /etc/mongod.conf.

Hence current changes happen in a configuration file that is not read
and his thus irrelevant.

Change-Id: I644d7f7a65ba8721e606eb869efede53bdeca7d7

Let's check for better wording and do some user-research/validation before committing to it."}, {'account_id': 5558, 'date': '2015-03-05 20:53:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

This is interesting.  But are you trying to solve a specific use case? Currently, retry happens on error anyway and on success it will break the retry loop.  But let's say the task err'd, this patch assumes the author knows what the error is and what the error will return in order to mark it as successful.  This also supports only a very narrow use case because when the task raise an exception, it also needs to pass the same data structure as success."}, {'account_id': 8731, 'date': '2015-03-06 05:57:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yes, guys, then let's pls continue the thread in ML ([openstack-dev] [mistral] Break_on in Retry policy) and discuss use cases, options etc."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-19 10:09:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1
